# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: gunpowder
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:gunpowder/adil-shahi] The **Sultanate of Bijapur** was an early modern kingdom in the western Deccan and South India, ruled by the Muslim **Adil Shahi** (or **Adilshahi**) dynasty.
[src:gunpowder/adil-shahi] Bijapur had been a *taraf* (province) of the Bahmani Kingdom prior to its independence in 1490 and before the kingdom's political decline in the last quarter of the 15th century.
[src:gunpowder/adil-shahi] It was one of the Deccan sultanates, the collective name of the kingdom's five successor states.
[src:gunpowder/adil-shahi] The Sultanate of Bijapur was one of the most powerful states on the Indian Subcontinent at its peak, second to the Mughal Empire which conquered it in 1686 under Aurangzeb.
[src:gunpowder/adil-shahi] After emigrating to the Bahmani Sultanate, Yusuf Adil Shah rose through the ranks to be appointed governor of the province of Bijapur.
[src:gunpowder/adil-shahi] In 1490, he created a *de facto* independent Bijapur state which became formally independent with the Bahmani collapse in 1518.
[src:gunpowder/adil-shahi] The Bijapur Sultanate's borders changed considerably throughout its history.
[src:gunpowder/adil-shahi] Its northern boundary remained relatively stable, straddling contemporary southern Maharashtra and northern Karnataka.
[src:gunpowder/adil-shahi] The sultanate expanded southward, its first major conquest the Raichur Doab after defeating the Vijayanagara Empire at the Battle of Talikota in 1565.
[src:gunpowder/adil-shahi] Later campaigns in the Karnatak and Carnatic extended Bijapur's borders and nominal authority as far south as Tanjore.
[src:gunpowder/adil-shahi] For most of its history, Bijapur was bounded on the west by the Portuguese state of Goa, on the east by the Sultanate of Golconda, on the north by the Ahmednagar Sultanate and on the south by the Vijayanagara Empire and its succeeding Nayaka dynasties.
[src:gunpowder/adil-shahi] The sultanate clashed incessantly with its neighbours.
[src:gunpowder/adil-shahi] After the allied victory against Vijayanagara at Talikota in 1565, the state expanded through its conquest of the neighbouring Bidar Sultanate in 1619.
[src:gunpowder/adil-shahi] The sultanate was then relatively stable, although it was damaged by the revolt of Shivaji (who founded an independent Maratha kingdom which become the Maratha Confederacy).
[src:gunpowder/adil-shahi] From the late 16th century, the greatest threat to Bijapur's security was the expansion of the Mughal Empire into the Deccan.
[src:gunpowder/adil-shahi] Agreements and treaties imposed Mughal suzerainty on the Adil Shahs, by stages, until Bijapur's formal recognition of Mughal authority in 1636.
[src:gunpowder/adil-shahi] The influence of their Mughal overlords and continual strife with the Marathas sapped the state of prosperity until the Mughal conquest of Bijapur in 1686.
[src:gunpowder/adil-shahi] The former Bahmani provincial capital of Bijapur remained the sultanate's capital throughout its existence.
[src:gunpowder/adil-shahi] After modest earlier developments, Ibrahim Adil Shah I and Ali Adil Shah I remodelled Bijapur with a citadel, city walls, and a congregational mosque.
[src:gunpowder/adil-shahi] Their successors, Ibrahim Adil Shah II, Mohammed Adil Shah and Ali Adil Shah II, added palaces, mosques, a mausoleum and other structures (considered some of the finest examples of Deccani and Indo-Islamic architecture) to the capital.
[src:gunpowder/adil-shahi] The founder of the dynasty, Yusuf Adil Shah, may have been a Georgian slave who was purchased by Mahmud Gawan.
[src:gunpowder/adil-shahi] Other historians have said that he is of Persian or Turkmen origin.
[src:gunpowder/adil-shahi] According to the contemporary historian Firishta, Yusuf was a son of the Ottoman Sultan Murad II; however, this is disputed by modern historians.
[src:gunpowder/adil-shahi] Another theory is that he was an Aq Qoyunlu Turkman.
[src:gunpowder/adil-shahi] Yusuf impressed Bahmani Sultan Muhammad Shah III, and he was appointed governor of Bijapur.
[src:gunpowder/adil-shahi] Yusuf took advantage of Bahmani decline to establish himself as an independent sultan at Bijapur in 1490, pursuing the same goal Malik Ahmad Nizam Shah I had that year.
[src:gunpowder/adil-shahi] He proclaimed Shia Islam as the official religion of his territorial holdings in 1503, following the lead of Shah Ismail of the Safavid dynasty.
[src:gunpowder/adil-shahi] Yusuf conquered and annexed the Bahmani *taraf* of Gulbarga the following year and reinstated his Shia mandate shortly afterwards, a year after he revoked it under threat of invasion.
[src:gunpowder/adil-shahi] A Portuguese Empire colonial expedition led by Afonso de Albuquerque exerted pressure on the major Adil Shahi port of Goa, conquering it in 1510; Yusuf retook the settlement two months later, but the Portuguese again conquered it in November of that year.
[src:gunpowder/adil-shahi] Yusuf died in 1510, between these two clashes with the Portuguese, when his son Ismail Adil Shah was a boy.
[src:gunpowder/adil-shahi] Ismail's regent, Kamal Khan, staged an unsuccessful coup against him; he was killed, and Ismail became the absolute ruler of Bijapur.
[src:gunpowder/adil-shahi] In 1514, a dispute over Gulbaraga province led the rulers of the Ahmednagar, Golconda, and Bidar Sultanates to unsuccessfully invade Ismail Adil Shah's provinces.
[src:gunpowder/adil-shahi] Krishnadevaraya, ruler of Vijayanagara, laid siege to the Bijapuri fort of Raichur in 1520.
[src:gunpowder/adil-shahi] The siege continued for three months until the emperor's encounter with Ismail, who attempted to end it.
[src:gunpowder/adil-shahi] Ismail was defeated by Krishnadevaraya in the Battle of Raichur; initially successful, with an advantage in artillery (in its first major appearance in a South Asian battle), Ismail was routed by the Vijayanagara forces in a surprise counter-attack which scattered much of his forces.
[src:gunpowder/adil-shahi] Soon after Ismail's retreat, Krishnadevaraya captured the Raichur fort.
[src:gunpowder/adil-shahi] In a later diplomatic conflict, Krishnadevaraya occupied Bijapur for an extended period and the sultan refused to see him.
[src:gunpowder/adil-shahi] Ismail invaded the territory of Amir Barid I of Bidar in 1529, besieging his capital; Aladdin Imad Shah of Berar unsuccessfully tried to mediate the conflict.
[src:gunpowder/adil-shahi] Amir Barid surrendered the fort of Bidar, which was looted by Ismail and his troops.
[src:gunpowder/adil-shahi] Ismail recaptured Raichur and Mudgal from Vijayanagara the following year, after the death of Krishnadevaraya.
[src:gunpowder/adil-shahi] Amir Barid agreed with Ismail to cede him the forts of Kalyani and Qandhar in exchange for Ismail's surrender of Bidar.
[src:gunpowder/adil-shahi] Ismail was succeeded in 1534 by Mallu Adil Shah, whose reign was short-lived.
[src:gunpowder/adil-shahi] Installed by a prominent Bijapuri noble, Asad Khan, he is noted for incompetence; Vijayanagara invaded the sultanate and seize the Raichur Doab from the Adil Shahis.
[src:gunpowder/adil-shahi] Mallu Adil Shah was soon blinded and removed from power.
[src:gunpowder/adil-shahi] Ibrahim Adil Shah I, Ismail's son, succeeded Mallu the following year.
[src:gunpowder/adil-shahi] He established Sunni Islam as the state religion and made anti-Westerner changes, abolishing the use of Persian in some administrative tasks (although it remained the sultanate's official language) and replacing many Westerners with Deccanis.
[src:gunpowder/adil-shahi] Ibrahim also invaded the Vijayanagara Empire; he pillaged a number of cities and besieged the capital, Vijayanagara, but did not seize any territory in the long term and returned home with only non-territorial rewards.
[src:gunpowder/adil-shahi] In another conflict with the Portuguese, Ibrahim ceded two ports in the fear that trade through Goa might be cut off from the Adil Shahis.
[src:gunpowder/adil-shahi] His kingdom was invaded four times by Ahmednagar Sultanate forces, the sultanate's greatest adversary.
[src:gunpowder/adil-shahi] The war was a defeat for the Bijapuri–Bidar side, who ceded a northern district of the Bijapur Sultanate to Ahmednagar.
[src:gunpowder/adil-shahi] Burhan and Ibrahim allowed Ahmednagar freedom to expand in Bidar if Bijapur had the same freedom to annex lands from Vijayanagara; Ibrahim imprisoned Ali Barid Shahi of Bidar despite their former alliance, although he was later freed by Jamsheed (who wanted a buffer state in the Deccan).
[src:gunpowder/adil-shahi] Burhan Nizam Shah besieged the Bijapuri city of Solapur four times, but did not retain it until a third invasion which occupied territory on the southern border.
[src:gunpowder/adil-shahi] Burhan advanced in a fourth invasion in 1553 with Vijayanagara almost to the Bijapuri capital, but retreated due to failing health.
[src:gunpowder/adil-shahi] Ali Adil Shah I, who ascended the throne in 1558, reestablished Shia Islam as the state religion.
[src:gunpowder/adil-shahi] He unsuccessfully asked Hussain Nizam Shah I for the return of Solapur and Kaliyani (both seized in Ahmednagari invasions) and then invaded the Nizam Shahi kingdom with assistance from Vijayanagara's *de facto* ruler Rama Raya and Ibrahim Qutb Shah, besieging Ahmednagar and other cities.
[src:gunpowder/adil-shahi] Hussain sued for peace in 1561, submitting to Rama Raya and returning Kaliyani to Ali Adil Shah.
[src:gunpowder/adil-shahi] In 1563, Hussain attempted to regain Kaliyani and again besieged it.
[src:gunpowder/adil-shahi] Ahmednagar was besieged by Ali, and Hussain was forced to abandon his siege of Kaliyani; the only beneficiary of the conflict was Vijayanagara, who gained territory from invading Golconda.
[src:gunpowder/adil-shahi] Vijayanagara negotiated additional land from Bijapur, including the cities of Yadgir and Bagalkote.
[src:gunpowder/adil-shahi] Wary of Vijayanagara's growing power, Ali allied his forces with the sultans of Golconda, Ahmednagar and Bidar (despite past conflicts) and defeated the Vijayanagara Empire in the 1565 Battle of Talikota.
[src:gunpowder/adil-shahi] Rama Raya was beheaded after his capture by Deccani forces.
[src:gunpowder/adil-shahi] Vijayanagara and nearby cities were sacked and looted (Vijayanagara for five to six months), and historian Hermann Goetz said that this prompted the emigration of much of Vijayanagara's population to Bijapur.
[src:gunpowder/adil-shahi] The Raichur Doab and its surrounding area were returned to Bijapur.
[src:gunpowder/adil-shahi] The Vijayanagara military was demolished, and the kingdom was a shell of its former self.
[src:gunpowder/adil-shahi] Ali I then fortified Bijapur with a wall, which facilitated the further centralization of authority.
[src:gunpowder/adil-shahi] Subsequent architectural projects encouraged the growth of the city and its skilled class.
[src:gunpowder/adil-shahi] Another conflict between Ahmednagar and Bijapur arose in 1567; although Ali invaded Ahmednagar and his forces occupied a number of forts, the war ended in a stalemate.
[src:gunpowder/adil-shahi] A 1570 conflict with the Portuguese began with the hope of expelling them from India, but Ali was defeated after a number of encounters the following year.
[src:gunpowder/adil-shahi] He then annexed more land from Vijayanagara in a campaign which lasted until 1575, conquering Adoni and much of the Carnatic.
[src:gunpowder/adil-shahi] Ali also began a campaign to capture the Karnatak; according to Richard M.
[src:gunpowder/adil-shahi] Eaton, his "armies destroyed two to three hundred Hindu temples" which were replaced with Shia buildings.
[src:gunpowder/adil-shahi] By 1576, land gained under Ali I had doubled the sultanate's holdings.
[src:gunpowder/adil-shahi] He forged diplomatic relations with the Mughals, Ottomans, and Safavids during his reign, which Eaton says brought the sultanate into the *dar al-islam*.
[src:gunpowder/adil-shahi] Ali I had no son, and his nine-year-old nephew Ibrahim II was set on the throne in 1580.
[src:gunpowder/adil-shahi] Control of the regency was contested by Kamal Khan and, later, by the Habshi Dilawar Khan (who reverted the state religion to Sunni Islam).
[src:gunpowder/adil-shahi] Dilawar was deposed by Ibrahim II in 1590.
[src:gunpowder/adil-shahi] Ibrahim's rule was characterised by prosperity and patronage; Sufism thrived, with its adherents and others flocking to Bijapur because of his talent as a musician and poet.
[src:gunpowder/adil-shahi] Ibrahim suppressed a 1594 rebellion by his brother, Ismail, who was aided by Burhan II of Ahmednagar.
[src:gunpowder/adil-shahi] Despite their past quarrels, the Adil Shahis formed an alliance in 1597 with Ahmednagar and Golconda to deter further Mughal advances in the Deccan.
[src:gunpowder/adil-shahi] The alliance, led by a Bijapuri general, was defeated despite a three-to-one numerical advantage.
[src:gunpowder/adil-shahi] Ahmednagar fell to the Mughals in 1600, but Ibrahim continued to support the eventually-successful resistance of Malik Ambar.
[src:gunpowder/adil-shahi] Ibrahim II founded the city of Nauraspur in 1599, three kilometers west of Bijapur, as a planned center of learning and art; never completed, it was destroyed in 1624 by Malik Ambar's forces.
[src:gunpowder/adil-shahi] In 1618, the sultan lost the fortress of Janjira to the independent Habshi state of western India.
[src:gunpowder/adil-shahi] The following year, Bijapur conquered the neighbouring Bidar Sultanate (although control of the state was achieved as early as 1580).
[src:gunpowder/adil-shahi] Bidar was in neither sphere of influence and Malik Ambar, *de facto* ruler of Ahmednagar, invaded Bijapur; after reaching the capital relatively unopposed, he withdrew.
[src:gunpowder/adil-shahi] In addition to his work on Nauraspur, the sultan built the Ibrahim Rauza.
[src:gunpowder/adil-shahi] Muhammad Adil Shah succeeded his father, Ibrahim II, in 1627.
[src:gunpowder/adil-shahi] Under Muhammad, the Sultanate of Bijapur reached its zenith.
[src:gunpowder/adil-shahi] The first Mughal invasion of the sultanate was in 1631 by Shah Jahan, who reached (and besieged) Bijapur but was ultimately unsuccessful.
[src:gunpowder/adil-shahi] In 1636, Bijapur signed a treaty agreeing to pay tribute to the Mughal emperor and acknowledge Mughal authority.
[src:gunpowder/adil-shahi] As a reward for this gesture, the recent Mughal conquest of Ahmednagar was partitioned between the two states.
[src:gunpowder/adil-shahi] The treaty began a period of relative peace with the Mughals, allowing for more southern conquests; Bijapur reached its territorial peak, with its borders stretching from the Arabian Sea to the Bay of Bengal.
[src:gunpowder/adil-shahi] Muhammad Adil Shah died in 1656 after a decade-long, paralyzing illness.
[src:gunpowder/adil-shahi] Ali Adil Shah II inherited a troubled kingdom which was invaded by Mughal forces in 1657 under viceroy Aurangzeb, who captured Bidar and other forts and reached Bijapur before retreating; Aurangzeb annexed much of the occupied territory, including Bidar.
[src:gunpowder/adil-shahi] The stability of the Bijapur Sultanate was again affected by trouble with the Marathas, who persisted with raids and rebellions.
[src:gunpowder/adil-shahi] Bijapuri general Afzal Khan was sent to subdue Shivaji in 1659, but he was murdered and his home fort of Pratapgarh was captured in a confrontation with Shivaji.
[src:gunpowder/adil-shahi] Despite further Maratha advances in the north, Ali continued his southern campaigns in the Karnatak and Carnatic and captured Thanjavur and other cities from the Nayakas from 1659 to 1663.
[src:gunpowder/adil-shahi] Sikandar Adil Shah, the last Adil Shahi sultan, ruled for fourteen troubled years.
[src:gunpowder/adil-shahi] His reign saw a number of civil wars, internal strife and unrest, particularly over his regency; he was four years old at his accession.
[src:gunpowder/adil-shahi] Khawas Khan, Sikandar's first regent and leader of the Deccani faction, took control of the state before his removal from power.
[src:gunpowder/adil-shahi] Shivaji founded an independent Maratha kingdom which became the Maratha Confederacy in 1674, with *de facto* control of much of the Adil Shahis' original territory in the Deccan.
[src:gunpowder/adil-shahi] He undid almost all the southern Bijapuri conquests over the following years, annexing the territory and renewing efforts to conquer the remaining Muslim Deccan states after Shivaji's death in 1680.
[src:gunpowder/adil-shahi] In April 1685, Mughal forces led by Aurangzeb began a siege of Bijapur; at its conclusion, on 12 September 1686, the Sultanate of Bijapur came to an end.
[src:gunpowder/adil-shahi] The capital and its surrounding territory were annexed into an eponymous *subah*, and Sikandar was sent into Mughal captivity.
[src:gunpowder/adil-shahi] The sultanate's architecture, a subset of Deccani architecture, was a variant of Indo-Islamic architecture influenced by that of the Middle East.
[src:gunpowder/adil-shahi] Adil Shahi architecture was of good quality with a localized, unique nature.
[src:gunpowder/adil-shahi] It was characterised by large domes and dargahs (Sufi shrines), complex turrets, geometric and Arabic (or Persian) calligraphic designs, and decorated friezes of tholobates.
[src:gunpowder/adil-shahi] Yusuf Adil Shah, the first sultan, began by expanding two dargahs at Gulbarga with minarets.
[src:gunpowder/adil-shahi] The first building characteristic of Adil Shahi architecture was a Jama Masjid built during the reign of Ibrahim Adil Shah I.
[src:gunpowder/adil-shahi] The primary Jami Masjid of Bijapur, built under Ali I, was commissioned in 1576.
[src:gunpowder/adil-shahi] The largest of any structure of its type in the Deccan when it was built, Eaton calls it "one of the most imposing and magnificent" in the region.
[src:gunpowder/adil-shahi] Under Ibrahim II, the sultanate's most prolific patron, Adil Shahi architecture focused on intricate carvings and detail and adopted Hindu–Muslim syncretism; this change is seen in the Malika Jahan Begum mosque built by the sultan in 1586.
[src:gunpowder/adil-shahi] His most notable commissioned work was the eponymous Ibrahim Rauza, completed in 1626, with a mosque built in honour of his wife and a mausoleum for his family.
[src:gunpowder/adil-shahi] Mohammed Adil Shah facilitated the creation of the Gol Gumbaz, his mausoleum and one of Bijapur's greatest monuments.
[src:gunpowder/adil-shahi] It is supported by large, arched recesses and a massive dome, the largest in the Islamic world when it was nearly completed at Muhammad's death in 1656.
[src:gunpowder/adil-shahi] The last major Adil Shahi architectural project was the Bara Kaman, Ali Adil Shah II's unfinished mausoleum, which halted construction with his death in 1672.
[src:gunpowder/adil-shahi] The Adil Shahis used miniature painting from the Bijapur school of Deccan painting.
[src:gunpowder/adil-shahi] Miniature painting was virtually nonexistent in the sultanate before the reign of Ali I, but became widespread under his rule and flourished under Ibrahim II and his successors.
[src:gunpowder/adil-shahi] The Bijapur school of painting was rooted in Persian miniature painting and culture, and was usually baroque in style.
[src:gunpowder/adil-shahi] In contrast to North Indian contemporary painting, it seldom depicted events and scenes of war but focused on atmospheric, picturesque fantasies and dreams, avoiding logic in general.
[src:gunpowder/adil-shahi] The Adil Shahi sultans promoted the development of writing in the Deccani language, and Bijapur was a center of its early literary evolution.
[src:gunpowder/adil-shahi] Ibrahim II, a skilled writer of Deccani Urdu literature, was one of its earliest proponents.
[src:gunpowder/adil-shahi] He wrote the *Kitab-i Nauras*, a Deccani musical poetry work, and patronized a number of poets and their work.
[src:gunpowder/adil-shahi] His poet laureate, the Persian Muhammad Zuhuri, wrote the *Saqinama*, a collection of lyric poetry.
[src:gunpowder/adil-shahi] After entering Ibrahim's service in 1604 and gaining his trust, Firishta followed the sultan's suggestion and wrote the *Tarikh-i Firishta*, his history of the medieval Deccan which is the basis for much modern historiography on the region and period.
[src:gunpowder/adil-shahi] Nusrati, a noted Deccani poet, wrote the later romantic poem *Gulshan-i 'Ishq* and a narrative of the sultan's conquests under the patronage of Ali Adil Shah II.
[src:gunpowder/adil-shahi] Nine sultans ruled the Sultanate of Bijapur from 1490 to 1686, with the title of Sultan of Bijapur.
[src:gunpowder/admiral] The word *admiral* in Middle English comes from Anglo-French *amiral*, "commander", from Medieval Latin *admiralis*, *admirallus*.
[src:gunpowder/admiral] The 1818 edition of Samuel Johnson's *A Dictionary of the English Language*, edited and revised by the Rev.
[src:gunpowder/admiral] The quote from John Minsheu's Dictionarie in Spanish and English (1599), given in Johnson's Dictionary, has been confirmed as being accurate.
[src:gunpowder/admiral] Those Phanariots who attained the princely position of dragoman of the fleet served under the Ottoman admiral having administration of the Aegean islands and the Anatolian coast.
[src:gunpowder/admiral] Central Command, introduced Vice Admiral Mark I.
[src:gunpowder/admiral] One alternate etymology proposes that the term admiral evolved, instead, from the title of Amīr al-Umarāʾ (أمير الأمراء).
[src:gunpowder/admiral] Under the reign of the Buyid dynasty (934 to 1062) of Iraq and Iran, the title of Amīr al-Umarāʾ, which means prince of princes, came to denote the heir-apparent, or crown prince.
[src:gunpowder/admiral] This alternate etymology states that the term was in use for the Greco-Arab naval leaders (e.g.
[src:gunpowder/admiral] Christodulus) in the Norman-Arab-Byzantine culture of Norman Sicily, which had formerly been ruled by Arabs, at least by the early 11th century.
[src:gunpowder/admiral] During this time, the Norman Roger II of Sicily (1095–1154) employed a Greek Christian, known as George of Antioch, who previously had served as a naval commander for several North African Muslim rulers.
[src:gunpowder/admiral] Roger styled George in Abbasid fashion as *Amir of Amirs*, or Amīr al-Umarāʾ, with the title becoming Latinized in the 13th century as *ammiratus ammiratorum*.
[src:gunpowder/admiral] The Sicilians and later the Genoese took the first two parts of the term from their Aragon opponents and used them as one word, *amiral*. .
[src:gunpowder/admiral] The French gave their sea commanders similar titles while in Portuguese and Spanish the word changed to *almirante*.
[src:gunpowder/admiral] As the word was used by people speaking Latin or Latin-based languages it gained the "d" and endured a series of different endings and spellings leading to the English spelling *admyrall* in the 14th century and to *admiral* by the 16th century.
[src:gunpowder/admiral] The etymology of a word does not suggest the antiquity of the word as it may have appeared in other languages with entirely different pronunciations.
[src:gunpowder/admiral] The Greek ναύαρχος, for instance, which is pronounced "naúarkhos", existed from very ancient times in Greece.
[src:gunpowder/admiral] The word "admiral" has come to be almost exclusively associated with the highest naval rank in most of the world's navies, equivalent to the army rank of general.
[src:gunpowder/admiral] However, this was not always the case; for example, in some European countries prior to the end of World War II, admiral was the third highest naval rank after general admiral and grand admiral.
[src:gunpowder/admiral] The rank of admiral has also been subdivided into various grades, several of which are historically extinct while others remain in use in most present-day navies.
[src:gunpowder/admiral] The Royal Navy used the colours red, white, and blue, in descending order to indicate seniority of its admirals until 1864; for example, Horatio Nelson's highest rank was vice-admiral of the white.
[src:gunpowder/admiral] The generic term for these naval equivalents of army generals is flag officer.
[src:gunpowder/admiral] Some navies have also used army-type titles for them, such as the Cromwellian "general at sea".
[src:gunpowder/admiral] While the rank is used in most of NATO countries, it is ranked differently depending on the country.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] Akbar gradually enlarged the Mughal Empire to include much of the Indian subcontinent through Mughal military, political, cultural, and economic dominance.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] To unify the vast Mughal state, Akbar established a centralised system of administration and adopted a policy of conciliating conquered rulers through marriage and diplomacy.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] To preserve peace and order in a religiously and culturally diverse empire, he adopted policies that won him the support of his non-Muslim subjects, including abolishing the sectarian tax and appointing them to high civil and military posts.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] Under Akbar, Mughal India developed a strong and stable economy, which tripled in size and wealth, leading to commercial expansion and greater patronage of an Indo-Persian culture.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] Akbar's courts at Delhi, Agra, and Fatehpur Sikri attracted holy men of many faiths, poets, architects, and artisans, and became known as centres of the arts, letters, and learning.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] Timurid and Perso-Islamic culture began to merge and blend with indigenous Indian elements into a distinct style of Mughal arts, including painting and architecture.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] Disillusioned with orthodox Islam and perhaps hoping to bring about religious unity within his empire, Akbar promulgated Din-i Ilahi, a syncretic creed derived mainly from Islam and Hinduism as well as elements of Zoroastrianism and Christianity.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] Akbar was succeeded as emperor by his son, Prince Salim, later known as Jahangir.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] After Mughal Emperor Humayun was defeated at Chausa (1539) and Kannauj (1540) by the forces of Sher Shah Suri, Humayun fled westward to modern-day Sindh.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] There, he met and married the 14-year-old Hamida Banu Begum, daughter of Shaikh Ali Akbar Jami, a Persian teacher of Humayun's younger brother Hindal Mirza.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] Jalal ud-din Muhammad Akbar was born to them the next year on 15 October 1542 (the fifth day of Rajab, 949 AH) at the Rajput Fortress of Amarkot in Rajputana (in modern-day Sindh), where his parents had been given refuge by the local Hindu ruler Rana Prasad.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] During the extended period of Humayun's exile, Akbar was brought up in Kabul by his paternal uncles, Kamran Mirza and Askari Mirza, and aunts, in particular, Kamran Mirza's wife.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] He spent his youth learning to hunt, run, and fight, and although he never learned to read or write, when he retired in the evening, he would have someone read to him.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] On 20 November 1551, Humayun's youngest brother, Hindal Mirza, died in a battle against Kamran Mirza's forces.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] Upon hearing the news of his brother's death, Humayun was overwhelmed with grief.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] Following the mourning period for Hindal in 1551, Humayun appointed the nine-year-old Akbar as governor of Ghazni and transferred to him the retainers, lands, and military command previously held by Hindal Mirza.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] Around the same time, Humayun arranged Akbar's betrothal to Hindal's daughter, Ruqaiya Sultan Begum.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] However, contemporary and later sources clarify that the transfer of Hindal's assets was a strategic elevation of Akbar within the Mughal imperial system, rather than a marital inheritance from this betrothal.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] The marriage itself was solemnized several years later in Jalandhar, Punjab, when both were about fourteen years old.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] Following chaos over the succession of Sher Shah Suri's son Islam Shah, Humayun reconquered Delhi in 1555, leading an army partly provided by his Persian ally Tahmasp I.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] Akbar's guardian, Bairam Khan, concealed his death to prepare for Akbar's succession.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] Akbar succeeded Humayun on 14 February 1556, while in the midst of a war against Sikandar Shah to reclaim the Mughal throne.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] In Kalanaur, Punjab, the 14-year-old Akbar was enthroned by Bairam Khan on a newly constructed platform (which still stands) and was proclaimed *Shahanshah* (Persian for "King of Kings").
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] Bairam Khan ruled on his behalf until he came of age.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] Akbar's military campaigns consolidated Mughal rule in the Indian subcontinent.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] Akbar introduced organisational changes to the *mansabdari* system, establishing a hierarchical scale of military and civil ranks.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] Organisational reforms were accompanied by innovations in cannons, fortifications, and the use of elephants.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] Akbar also took an interest in matchlocks and effectively employed them during various conflicts.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] He sought the help of the Ottomans, as well as Europeans, especially the Portuguese and Italians, in procuring advanced firearms and artillery.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] Akbar's vizier Abul Fazl once declared that "with the exception of Turkey, there is perhaps no country in which its guns has more means of securing the Government than [India]." Scholars and historians have used the term "gunpowder empire" to analyse the success of the Mughals in India.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] Akbar's father Humayun had regained control of the Punjab, Delhi, and Agra with Safavid support, but Mughal rule was still precarious when Akbar took the throne.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] When the Surs reconquered Agra and Delhi following the death of Humayun, Akbar's young age and the lack of military assistance from the Mughal stronghold of Kabul—which was in the midst of an invasion by the ruler of Badakhshan, Prince Mirza Suleiman—aggravated the situation.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] When his regent, Bairam Khan, called a council of war to marshall the Mughal forces, none of Akbar's chieftains approved.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] Bairam Khan was ultimately able to prevail over the nobles and it was decided that the Mughals would march against the strongest of the Sur rulers, Sikandar Shah Suri, in Punjab.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] Delhi was left under the regency of Tardi Baig Khan.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] Sikandar Shah Suri, his army weakened by earlier lost battles, withdrew to avoid combat as the Mughal army approached.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] Akbar also faced Hemu, a minister and general of one of the Sur rulers, who had proclaimed himself Hindu emperor and expelled the Mughals from the Indo-Gangetic Plains.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] Urged by Bairam Khan, who re-marshalled the Mughal army before Hemu could consolidate his position, Akbar marched on Delhi to reclaim it.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] His army, led by Bairam Khan, defeated Hemu and the Sur army on 5 November 1556 at the Second Battle of Panipat, 50 miles (80 km) north of Delhi.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] Soon after the battle, Mughal forces occupied Delhi and then Agra.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] Akbar made a triumphant entry into Delhi, where he stayed for a month.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] Then, he and Bairam Khan returned to Punjab to deal with Sikandar Shah Suri, who had become active again.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] In the next six months, the Mughals won another major battle against Sikander, who fled east to Bengal.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] Akbar and his forces occupied Lahore and then seized Multan in the Punjab.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] In 1558, Akbar took possession of Ajmer, the aperture to Rajputana, after the defeat and flight of its Muslim ruler.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] The Mughals also besieged and defeated the Sur forces in control of Gwalior Fort, a stronghold north of the Narmada river.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] Royal begums (ladies), along with the families of Mughal amirs, were brought from Kabul to India at the time, "so that men might become settled and be restrained in some measure from departing to a country to which they were accustomed", according to Fazl.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] Akbar made clear that he would stay in India, reintroducing the historical legacy of the Timurid Renaissance, in contrast to his grandfather and father, who reigned as transient rulers.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] By 1559, the Mughals had launched a drive to the south into Rajputana and Malwa.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] However, Akbar's disputes with his regent, Bairam Khan, temporarily put an end to the expansion.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] The young emperor, at the age of eighteen, wanted to take a more active part in managing the Empire's affairs.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] Urged on by his foster mother, Maham Anga, and other relatives, Akbar dismissed Bairam Khan following a dispute at court in the spring of 1560 and ordered him to leave on Hajj to Mecca.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] Bairam Khan was prepared to comply, but people who resented him and hoped for his downfall goaded him into rebellion against Akbar.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] Bairam Khan was defeated by the Mughal army in the Punjab and forced to submit.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] Akbar forgave him and gave him the option of either continuing in his court or resuming his pilgrimage; Bairam Khan chose the latter.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] Bairam Khan was assassinated on his way to Mecca, by a group of Afghans led by Mubarak Khan Lohani, whose father had been killed while fighting with the Mughals at the Battle of Machhiwara in 1555.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] In 1560, Akbar resumed military operations.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] A Mughal army under the command of his foster brother, Adham Khan, and a Mughal commander, Pir Muhammad Khan, began the Mughal conquest of Malwa.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] The Afghan ruler, Baz Bahadur, was defeated at the Battle of Sarangpur and fled to Khandesh for refuge, leaving behind his harem, treasure, and war elephants.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] Akbar personally rode to Malwa to confront Adham Khan and relieve him of command.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] Pir Muhammad Khan was then sent in pursuit of Baz Bahadur, but was beaten back by the alliance of the rulers of Khandesh and Berar.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] Baz Bahadur temporarily regained control of Malwa until, in the next year, Akbar sent another Mughal army to invade and annexe the kingdom.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] Malwa became a province of the nascent imperial administration of Akbar's regime.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] Baz Bahadur survived as a refugee at various courts until, eight years later in 1570, he took service under Akbar.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] When Adham Khan confronted Akbar following another dispute in late 1561, the emperor threw him from a terrace into the palace courtyard at Agra.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] Still alive, Adham Khan was dragged up and thrown to the courtyard once again by Akbar to ensure his death.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] After Adham Khan's death, Akbar distributed authority among specialised ministerial posts relating to different aspects of imperial governance to prevent any one noble from becoming too powerful.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] When a powerful clan of Uzbek chiefs broke out in rebellion in 1564, Akbar routed them in Malwa and then Bihar.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] He pardoned the rebellious leaders, hoping to conciliate them, but they rebelled again; Akbar quelled their second uprising.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] Following a third revolt, during which they proclaimed Mirza Muhammad Hakim—Akbar's brother and the Mughal ruler of Kabul— to be their king, several Uzbek chieftains were slain.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] Simultaneously, the Mirzas, a group of Akbar's distant cousins who held important fiefs near Agra, rebelled and were defeated by Akbar.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] Several rebel leaders were trampled to death under elephants.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] In 1566, Akbar moved to meet the forces of his brother, Muhammad Hakim, who had marched into the Punjab with the intention of seizing the imperial throne.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] Following a brief confrontation, Muhammad Hakim accepted Akbar's supremacy and retreated back to Kabul.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] In 1564, Mughal forces began the conquest of Garha, a thinly populated, hilly area in central India that was of interest to the Mughals because of its herd of wild elephants.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] The territory was ruled over by Raja Vir Narayan, a minor, and his mother, Durgavati, a Rajput warrior queen of the Gonds.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] Akbar did not personally lead the campaign because he was preoccupied with the Uzbek rebellion, leaving the expedition in the hands of Asaf Khan, the Mughal governor of Kara.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] Durgavati committed suicide after her defeat at the Battle of Damoh, while Raja Vir Narayan was slain at the Fall of Chauragarh, the mountain fortress of the Gonds.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] The Mughals seized immense wealth, including an uncalculated amount of gold and silver, jewels, and 1,000 elephants.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] Kamala Devi, a younger sister of Durgavati, was sent to the Mughal harem.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] The brother of Durgavati's deceased husband was installed as the Mughal administrator of the region.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] As with Malwa, Akbar entered into a dispute with his vassals over the conquest of Gondwana.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] Asaf Khan was accused of keeping most of the treasures and sending back only 200 elephants to Akbar.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] When summoned to give accounts, he fled Gondwana.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] He went first to the Uzbeks, then returned to Gondwana where he was pursued by Mughal forces.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] Finally, he submitted and Akbar restored him to his previous position.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] In January 1564, an assassin shot an arrow at Akbar, which pierced his right shoulder, as he was returning from a visit to the Dargah of Hazrat Nizamuddin near Delhi.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] The Emperor ordered the apprehended assassin, a slave of Mirza Sharfuddin—a noble in Akbar's court whose recent rebellion had been suppressed—to be beheaded.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] Having established Mughal rule over northern India, Akbar turned his attention to the conquest of Rajputana, which was strategically important as it was a rival centre of power that flanked the Indo-Gangetic plains.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] The Mughals had already established domination over parts of northern Rajputana in Mewat, Ajmer, and Nagor.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] Akbar sought to conquer Rajputana's heartlands, which had rarely previously submitted to the Muslim rulers of the Delhi Sultanate.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] Beginning in 1561, the Mughals actively engaged the Rajputs in warfare and diplomacy.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] Most Rajput states accepted Akbar's suzerainty; however, the rulers of Mewar and Marwar—Udai Singh II and Chandrasen Rathore—remained outside the imperial fold.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] Udai Singh was descended from the Sisodia ruler, Rana Sanga, who had fought Babur at the Battle of Khanwa in 1527.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] As the head of the Sisodia clan, he possessed the highest ritual status of all the Rajput kings and chieftains in India.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] The Mughals viewed defeating Udai Singh as essential to asserting their imperial authority among the Rajputs.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] During this period of his reign, Akbar was still devoted to Islam and sought to impress the superiority of his faith over what were regarded by contemporaries as the most prestigious warriors in Hinduism.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] In 1567, Akbar attacked the Chittor Fort in Mewar.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] The fortress-capital of Mewar was of strategic importance as it lay on the shortest route from Agra to Gujarat and was also considered a key to holding the interior parts of Rajputana.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] Udai Singh retreated to the hills of Mewar, leaving two Rajput warriors, Jaimal and Patta, in charge of the defence of his capital.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] Chittorgarh fell in February 1568 after a siege of four months.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] Akbar had the surviving defenders and 30,000 non-combatants massacred and their heads displayed upon towers erected throughout the region to demonstrate his authority.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] Thereafter, Udai Singh never ventured out of his mountain refuge in Mewar.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] A legend, oft repeated by historians, has grown up that Akbar set up statues of Jaimal and Patta mounted on elephants at a gate of his fort in Agra to commemorate his victory.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] There are records from his time of two statues of elephants with their riders outside the eastern gate of his fort in Agra, but these may have had nothing to do with the Rajputs of Chittor, they may have been purely decorative.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] Indologist Eugenia Vanina found no account that connects the statues to Jaimal and Patta until a 1629 chronicle by Dutch merchants.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] She believes that the narrative that the statues were monuments grew up to "provide ideological, social and psychological substantiation" of the alliance between the Mughals and the Rajputs.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] The fall of Chittorgarh was followed up by a Mughal attack on the Ranthambore Fort in 1568.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] Ranthambore was held by the Hada Rajputs and reputed to be the most powerful fortress in India.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] However, it fell only after a couple of months.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] At that point, most of the Rajput kings had submitted to the Mughals; only the clans of Mewar continued to resist.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] Udai Singh's son and successor, Maharana Pratap, was later defeated by the Mughals at the Battle of Haldighati in 1576.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] Akbar would celebrate his conquest of Rajputana by laying the foundation of a new capital, 23 miles (37 km) west-southwest of Agra, in 1569.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] It was called Fatehpur Sikri, or the "City of Victory".
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] Pratap Singh continued to attack the Mughals and was able to retain most of his kingdom during Akbar's reign.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] Akbar's next military objectives were the conquest of Gujarat and Bengal, which connected India with the trading centres of Asia, Africa, and Europe through the Arabian Sea and the Bay of Bengal.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] Gujarat had also been a haven for rebellious Mughal nobles.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] In Bengal, the Afghans still held considerable influence under their ruler, Sulaiman Khan Karrani.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] Akbar first moved against Gujarat, which lay in the crook of the Mughal provinces of Rajputana and Malwa.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] Gujarat possessed areas of rich agricultural production in its central plain, an impressive output of textiles and other industrial goods, and the busiest seaports of India.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] Akbar intended to link the maritime state with the massive resources of the Indo-Gangetic plains.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] Akbar's ostensible *casus belli* for warring with Gujarat was that the rebel Mirzas, who had previously been driven out of India, were now operating out of a base in southern Gujarat.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] Moreover, Akbar had received invitations from cliques in Gujarat to oust the reigning king, which further served as justification for his military expedition.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] In 1572, Akbar moved to occupy Ahmedabad, the capital, and other northern cities, and was proclaimed the lawful sovereign of Gujarat.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] By 1573, he had driven out the Mirzas who, after offering token resistance, fled for refuge in the Deccan.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] Surat, the commercial capital of the region, and other coastal cities soon capitulated to the Mughals.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] The king, Muzaffar Shah III, was caught hiding in a corn field; he was pensioned off by Akbar with a small allowance.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] Akbar then returned to Fatehpur Sikiri, where he built the Buland Darwaza to commemorate his victories.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] But, a rebellion by Afghan nobles supported by the Rajput ruler of Idar, as well a resurgence of the Mirzas (who retook Cambay, Broach, and Surat), forced his return to Gujarat.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] Akbar crossed Rajputana and reached Ahmedabad in 11 days—a journey that normally took six weeks.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] The outnumbered Mughal army won a decisive victory on 2 September 1573.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] Akbar slew the rebel leaders and erected a tower out of their severed heads.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] The conquest and subjugation of Gujarat proved highly profitable for the Mughals; after expenses, the territory yielded a revenue of more than five million rupees annually to Akbar's treasury.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] After conquering Gujarat, the remaining centre of Afghan power was Bengal.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] In 1572, Sulaiman Khan's son, Daud Khan, succeeded him.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] Daud Khan defined Mughal rule, assuming the insignia of royalty and ordering that the khutbah be proclaimed in his name, rather than Akbar's.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] Munim Khan, the Mughal governor of Bihar, was ordered to chastise Daud Khan.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] Eventually, Akbar himself set out to Bengal, and in 1574, the Mughals seized Patna from Daud Khan, who fled to Bengal.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] Akbar then returned to Fatehpur Sikri and left his generals to finish the campaign.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] The Mughal army was subsequently victorious at the Battle of Tukaroi in 1575, which led to the annexation of Bengal and parts of Bihar that had been under the dominion of Daud Khan.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] Only Orissa was left in the hands of the Karrani dynasty, albeit as a fief of the Mughal Empire.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] A year later, however, Daud Khan rebelled and attempted to regain Bengal.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] He was defeated by the Mughal general Khan Jahan Quli and fled into exile.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] Daud Khan was later captured and executed by Mughal forces.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] His severed head was sent to Akbar, while his limbs were gibbeted at Tandah, the Mughal capital in Bengal.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] Following his conquests of Gujarat and Bengal, Akbar was preoccupied with domestic concerns.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] He did not leave Fatehpur Sikri on a military campaign until 1581, when Punjab was again invaded by his brother, Mirza Muhammad Hakim.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] Akbar expelled his brother to Kabul and waged a campaign to remove him from power.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] At the same time, Akbar's nobles were resisting leaving India to administer the Empire's holdings in Afghanistan; they were, according to Abul Fazl "afraid of the cold of Afghanistan".
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] Likewise, Hindu officers in the Mughal army were inhibited by the traditional taboo against crossing the Indus.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] To encourage them, Akbar provided them with pay eight months in advance.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] In August 1581, Akbar seized Kabul and took up residence at Babur's old citadel.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] He stayed there for three weeks and his brother fled into the mountains.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] Akbar left Kabul in the hands of his sister, Bakht-un-Nissa Begum, and returned to India.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] He then pardoned his brother, who took up de facto control of the Mughal administration in Kabul; Bakht-un-Nissa continued to be the official governor.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] In 1585, after Muhammad Hakim died, Kabul passed into the hands of Akbar and was officially incorporated as a province of the Mughal Empire.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] The Kabul expedition was the beginning of a long period of activity over the northern frontiers of the empire.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] For thirteen years, beginning in 1585, Akbar remained in the north, shifting his capital to Lahore while he dealt with challenges from Uzbek tribes, which had driven his grandfather, Babur, out of Central Asia.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] The Uzbeks were organised under Abdullah Khan Shaybanid, a military chieftain who had seized Badakhshan and Balkh from Akbar's distant Timurid relatives, and whose troops challenged the northwestern frontiers of the Mughal Empire.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] The Uzbeks also subsidised Afghan tribes on the border that were hostile to the Mughals.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] The tribes felt challenged by the Yusufzai of Bajaur and Swat and were motivated by a new religious leader, Bayazid, the founder of the Roshaniyya sect.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] In 1586, Akbar negotiated a pact with Abdullah Khan in which the Mughals agreed to remain neutral during the Uzbek invasion of Safavid-held Khorasan.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] In return, Abdullah Khan agreed to refrain from supporting, subsidising, or offering refuge to the Afghan tribes hostile to the Mughals.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] Akbar, in turn, began a series of campaigns to pacify the Yusufzais and other rebels.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] Akbar ordered Zain Khan to lead an expedition against the Afghan tribes.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] Raja Birbal, a renowned minister in Akbar's court, was also given military command.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] The expedition failed, and on their retreat from the mountains, Birbal and his entourage were ambushed and killed by Afghans at the Malandarai Pass in February 1586.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] Akbar immediately fielded new armies to reinvade the Yusufzai lands under the command of Raja Todar Mal.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] Over the next six years, the Mughals contained the Yusufzai in the mountain valleys, forcing the submission of many chiefs in Swat and Bajaur.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] Dozens of forts were built and occupied to secure the region.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] Despite his pact with the Uzbeks, Akbar nurtured a secret hope of reconquering Central Asia, but Badakshan and Balkh remained firmly part of the Uzbek dominion.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] Abdullah Khan died in 1598 and the last of the rebellious Afghan tribes were subdued by 1600.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] The Roshaniyya movement was suppressed, its leaders were captured or driven into exile, and the Afridi and Orakzai tribes which had risen up under them were subjugated.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] Jalaluddin, the son of the Roshaniyya movement's founder, Bayazid, was killed in 1601 in a fight with Mughal troops near Ghazni.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] While Akbar was in Lahore dealing with the Uzbeks, he sought to subjugate the Indus valley to secure the frontier provinces.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] In 1585, he sent an army to conquer Kashmir in the upper Indus basin after Yousuf Shah, the reigning king of the Shia Chak dynasty, refused to send his son as a hostage to the Mughal court.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] Yousuf Shah surrendered immediately to the Mughals, but another of his sons, Yaqub Shah, crowned himself as king, leading a resistance against the Mughal armies.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] In June 1589, Akbar travelled from Lahore to Srinagar to receive the surrender of Yaqub and his rebel forces.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] Baltistan and Ladakh, which were Tibetan provinces adjacent to Kashmir, pledged their allegiance to Akbar.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] The Mughals also moved to conquer Sindh in the lower Indus valley.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] Since 1574, the northern fortress of Bhakkar had remained under imperial control.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] In 1586, the Mughal governor of Multan tried and failed to secure the capitulation of Mirza Jani Beg, the independent ruler of Thatta in southern Sindh.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] Akbar responded by sending a Mughal army to besiege Sehwan, the river capital of the region.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] Jani Beg mustered a large army to meet the Mughals.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] The outnumbered Mughal forces defeated the Sindhi forces at the Battle of Sehwan.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] After suffering further defeats, Jani Beg surrendered to the Mughals in 1591, and in 1593, paid homage to Akbar in Lahore.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] As early as 1586, about half a dozen Baluchi chiefs, under nominal Pani Afghan rule, had been persuaded to subordinate themselves to Akbar.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] In preparation for taking Kandahar from the Safavids, Akbar ordered the Mughal forces to conquer the rest of the Afghan-held parts of Baluchistan in 1595.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] The Mughal general Mir Masum led an attack on the stronghold of Sibi, which was northeast of Quetta, and defeated a coalition of local chieftains in battle.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] They were required to acknowledge Mughal supremacy and attend Akbar's court.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] As a result, the modern-day Pakistani and Afghan parts of Baluchistan, including the Makran coast, became a part of the Mughal Empire.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] Kandahar (also known as the ancient Indian kingdom of Gandhara) had connections with the Mughals from the time of the Empire's ancestor, Timur, the warlord who had conquered much of Western, Central, and parts of South Asia in the 14th century.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] However, the Safavids considered it to be an appanage of the Persian-ruled territory of Khorasan, and declared its association with the Mughal emperors to be a usurpation.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] In 1558, while Akbar was consolidating his rule over northern India, Safavid Shah Tahmasp I seized Kandahar and expelled its Mughal governor.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] The recovery of Kandahar had not been a priority for Akbar, but after his military activity in the northern frontiers, he moved to restore Mughal control.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] At the time, the region was also under threat from the Uzbeks, but the Emperor of Persia, himself beleaguered by the Ottoman Turks, was unable to send reinforcements.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] In 1593, Akbar received the exiled Safavid prince, Rostam Mirza.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] Rostam Mirza pledged allegiance to the Mughals; he was granted a rank (mansab) of command over 5,000 men and received Multan as a jagir.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] The Safavid prince and governor of Kandahar, Mozaffar Hosayn, also agreed to defect to the Mughals.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] Hosayn, who was in an adversary relationship with his overlord, Shah Abbas, was granted a rank of 5,000 men, and his daughter Kandahari Begum was married to Akbar's grandson, the Mughal prince Khurram.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] Kandahar was secured in 1595 with the arrival of a garrison headed by the Mughal general, Shah Bayg Khan.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] The reconquest of Kandahar did not overtly disturb Mughal-Persian relations.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] Akbar and the Persian Shah continued to exchange ambassadors and presents.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] However, the power equation between the two had now changed in favour of the Mughals.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] In 1593, Akbar began military operations against the Deccan Sultans, who had not submitted to his authority.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] He besieged Ahmednagar Fort in 1595, forcing Chand Bibi to cede Berar.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] A subsequent revolt forced Akbar to take the fort in August 1600.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] Akbar occupied Burhanpur and besieged Asirgarh Fort in 1599, and took it on 17 January 1601, when Miran Bahadur Shah of the Khandesh Sultanate refused to relinquish Khandesh.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] Akbar then established the Subahs of Ahmadnagar, Berar, and Khandesh under Prince Daniyal.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] "By the time of his death in 1605, Akbar controlled a broad sweep of territory from the Bay of Bengal to Kandahar and Badakshan.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] Akbar's system of central government was based on the system that had evolved since the Delhi Sultanate.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] Akbar reorganised the sections with a detailed set of regulations.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] The revenue department was headed by a *wazir*, responsible for finances and management of *jagir* and *inam* land.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] The head of the military was called the *mir bakshi*, appointed from among the leading nobles of the court.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] The *mir bakshi* was in charge of intelligence gathering, and made recommendations to the emperor for military appointments and promotion.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] The *mir saman* was in charge of the imperial household, including the harems, and supervised the functioning of the court and royal bodyguard.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] The judiciary was a separate organisation headed by a chief *qazi*, who was also responsible for religious beliefs and practices.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] Akbar reformed the administration land revenues by adopting a system that had been used by Sher Shah Suri.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] The village continued to remain the primary unit of revenue assessment.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] Cultivated areas were measured and taxed through fixed rates—on the basis of prices prevailing the imperial court—based on the type of crop and productivity.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] This system burdened the peasantry because prices at the imperial court were often higher than those in the countryside.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] Akbar also introduced a decentralised system of annual assessment, which resulted in corruption among local officials.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] The system was abandoned in 1580 and replaced with the **dahsala** (also known as **zabti**), under which revenue was calculated as one-third of the average produce of the previous ten years, to be paid to the state in cash.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] This system was later refined, taking into account local prices and grouping areas with similar productivity into assessment circles.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] Remission was given to peasants when the harvest failed during times of flood or drought.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] The **dahsala** system was set out by Raja Todar Mal, who also served as a revenue officer under Sher Shah Suri, in a detailed memorandum submitted to the emperor in 1582–1583.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] Other local methods of assessment continued in some areas.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] Lands which were fallow or uncultivated were assessed at concessional rates.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] Akbar also encouraged the improvement and extension of agriculture.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] Zamindars were required to provide loans and agricultural implements in times of need, and to encourage farmers to plough as much land as possible and sow high-quality seeds.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] In turn, the zamindars were given a hereditary right to collect a share of the produce.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] Peasants had a hereditary right to cultivate the land as long as they paid the land revenue.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] Revenue officials were guaranteed only three-quarters of their salary, with the remaining quarter dependent on their full realisation of the revenue assessed.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] Akbar organised his army and the nobility by means of a system called the *mansabdari*.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] Under this system, each officer in the army was assigned a rank (a *mansabdar*) and assigned a number of cavalry, which he was required to supply to the imperial army.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] The *mansabdars* were divided into 33 classes.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] The top three commanding ranks, ranging from 7,000 to 10,000 troops, were normally reserved for princes.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] Ranks between 10 and 5,000 were assigned to other members of the nobility.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] The empire's permanent standing army was small and the imperial forces mostly consisted of contingents maintained by the *mansabdars*.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] Persons were normally appointed to a low *mansab* and then promoted based on merit and the favour of the emperor.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] Each *mansabdar* was required to maintain a certain number of cavalrymen and twice that number of horses.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] The number of horses was greater because they had to be rested and rapidly replaced in times of war.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] Akbar employed strict measures to ensure that the quality of the armed forces was maintained at a high level; horses were regularly inspected and usually only Arabian horses were employed.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] The *mansabdars* were the highest paid military service in the world at the time.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] Akbar was a follower of Salim Chishti, a holy man who lived in the region of Sikri near Agra.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] Believing the area to be lucky, Akbar had a mosque constructed there for the use of the priest.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] The city was soon abandoned and the capital was moved to Lahore in 1585.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] Historians have advanced several reasons for the move, including an insufficient or poor quality water supply at Fatehpur Sikri, Akbar's campaigns in the northwest areas of the Empire or loss of interest.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] In 1599, Akbar moved his capital back to Agra, where he ruled until his death.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] Akbar was a patron of the arts and culture.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] He had Sanskrit literature translated and participated in native festivals.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] Akbar established the library of Fatehpur Sikri exclusively for women, and he decreed the establishment of schools for the education of both Muslims and Hindus throughout the realm.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] He also encouraged bookbinding to become a high art.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] Akbar's government prioritised commercial expansion, encouraging traders, providing protection and security for transactions, and levying a low custom duty to stimulate foreign trade.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] It also required that local administrators provide restitution to traders for goods stolen while in their territories.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] To minimise such incidents, bands of highway police called **rahdars** were enlisted to patrol roads and ensure the safety of traders.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] Other active measures taken included the construction and protection of routes of commerce and communications.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] Akbar made concerted efforts to improve roads to facilitate the use of wheeled vehicles through the Khyber Pass, the most popular route frequented by traders and travellers journeying from Kabul into Mughal India.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] He also strategically occupied the northwestern cities of Multan and Lahore in Punjab and constructed forts, such as the one at Attock near the crossing of the Grand Trunk Road and the Indus river.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] He also constructed a network of smaller forts called *thanas* throughout the frontier to secure the overland trade route with Persia and Central Asia.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] He also established an international trading business for his chief consort, Mariam-uz-Zamani, who ran an extensive trade of indigo, spices, and cotton to Gulf nations through merchant's vessels.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] Akbar introduced coins with decorative features, including floral motifs, dotted borders, and quatrefoil.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] The coins were issued in both round and square shapes, including a unique 'mehrab' (lozenge) shaped coin.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] Akbar's portrait type gold coin (Mohur) is generally attributed to his son, Prince Salim (later Emperor Jahangir), who had rebelled and then sought reconciliation by minting and presenting his father with gold Mohurs bearing Akbar's portrait.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] During the latter part of Akbar's reign, coins portrayed the concept of Akbar's newly promoted religion, with the Ilahi type and Jalla Jalal-Hu types.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] Prior to Akbar's reign, marriages between Hindu princesses and Muslim kings failed to produce stable relations between the families involved; the women were lost to their families and did not return after marriage.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] Akbar departed from that practice, providing that the Hindu Rajputs who married their daughters or sisters to him would be treated equally to his Muslim fathers- and brothers-in-law, except that they would not be allowed to dine or pray with him or take Muslim wives.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] Akbar also made those Rajputs members of his court.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] Some Rajputs considered marriage to Akbar a sign of humiliation.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] The Kacchwaha Rajput, Raja Bharmal, of the small kingdom of Amer, and an early member of Akbar's court, allied with Akbar by giving his daughter, Mariam-uz-Zamani—who would go on to be Akbar's favorite wife—in marriage to Akbar.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] Bharmal was made a noble of high rank in the imperial court, and subsequently, his son Bhagwant Das and grandson Man Singh also rose to high ranks in the nobility.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] Other Rajput kingdoms also established matrimonial alliances with Akbar, but Akbar did not insist upon matrimony as a precondition for forming alliances.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] When Akbar met with the Hada leader, Surjan Hada, to effect an alliance, Surjan accepted on the condition that Akbar could not marry any of his daughters.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] Consequently, no matrimonial alliance was entered into, but Surjan was made a noble and placed in charge of Garh-Katanga.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] Two major Rajput clans remained aloof—the Sisodiyas of Mewar and Hadas of Ranthambore.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] The political effect of these alliances was significant.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] The interaction between Hindu and Muslim nobles in the imperial court resulted in an exchange of thoughts and a blending of the two cultures.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] Newer generations of the Mughal line also represented a merger of Mughal and Rajput blood, thereby strengthening ties between the two.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] As a result, the Rajputs became the strongest allies of the Mughals, and Rajput soldiers and generals fought for the Mughal army under Akbar, leading it in several campaigns, including the conquest of Gujarat in 1572.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] Akbar's policy of religious tolerance ensured that employment in the imperial administration was open to all on merit, irrespective of creed, strengthening his imperial rule.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] Akbar's daughter Meherunnissa was rumoured to be enamored of Tansen and might have played a role in his coming to Akbar's court.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] Tansen converted to Islam from Hinduism, apparently on the eve of his marriage with Akbar's daughter.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] At the time of Akbar's ascension in 1556, the Portuguese had established several fortresses and factories on the western coast of the subcontinent, and largely controlled navigation and sea trade in that region.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] As a consequence, all other trading entities were subject to the terms and conditions of the Portuguese, which was resented by rulers and traders, including Bahadur Shah of Gujarat.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] In 1572, the Mughal Empire annexed Gujarat and acquired its first access to the sea, but local officials informed Akbar that the Portuguese had begun to exert control in the Indian Ocean.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] Akbar obtained a *cartaz* (permit) from the Portuguese to sail in the Persian Gulf region.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] At the initial meeting of the Mughals and the Portuguese during the Siege of Surat in 1572, the Portuguese, recognising the superior strength of the Mughal army, chose to adopt diplomacy instead of war.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] The Portuguese Governor, upon the request of Akbar, sent him an ambassador to establish friendly relations.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] Akbar accepted the offer of diplomacy, but the Portuguese continually asserted their authority and power in the Indian Ocean; Akbar expressed concern when he was required to request a permit from the Portuguese before any ships from the Mughal Empire could depart for the Hajj to Mecca and Medina.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] In 1573, Akbar issued a *firman* directing Mughal administrative officials in Gujarat not to provoke the Portuguese in the territory they held in Daman.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] The Portuguese, in turn, issued passes for members of Akbar's family to go on Hajj to Mecca.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] The Portuguese made mention of the extraordinary status of the vessel and the special status to be accorded to its occupants.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] Akbar was unsuccessful in purchasing compact artillery pieces from the Portuguese, hindering his efforts to establish a Mughal navy along the Gujarat coast.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] In September 1579, Jesuits from Goa were invited to visit the court of Akbar.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] The emperor had his scribes translate the New Testament and granted the Jesuits freedom to preach the Gospel.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] One of his sons, Sultan Murad Mirza, was entrusted to Antoni de Montserrat for his education.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] While debating at court, the Jesuits denigrated Islam and Muhammad.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] Their comments enraged the Imams and Ulama, who objected to the remarks, but Akbar ordered their comments to be recorded.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] This event was followed by a rebellion of Muslim clerics in 1581 led by Mullah Muhammad Yazdi and Muiz-ul-Mulk, the chief Qadi of Bengal; the rebels sought to overthrow Akbar and put his brother Mirza Muhammad Hakim on the Mughal throne.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] Akbar successfully defeated the rebels, but he became more cautious about inviting guests to his court, seeking advice from his counselors.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] In 1555, while Akbar was still a child, the Ottoman Admiral Seydi Ali Reis visited the Mughal Emperor Humayun.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] In 1569, during the early years of Akbar's rule, Ottoman Admiral Kurtoğlu Hızır Reis visited the Empire.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] These Ottoman admirals sought to end the growing threats of the Portuguese Empire during their Indian Ocean campaigns.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] During his reign, Akbar six documents addressing the Ottoman Sultan Suleiman the Magnificent.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] In 1576, Akbar sent a contingent of pilgrims on Hajj, led by Khwaja Sultan Naqshbandi, with 600,000 rupees and 12,000 *khalats* (honorific robes) for the needy of Mecca and Medina.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] In October 1576, Akbar sent a delegation, which included his aunt Gulbadan Begum and his consort Salima, on Hajj by two ships, including an Ottoman vessel, from Surat, which reached the port of Jeddah in 1577 and then proceeded to Mecca and Medina.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] Four more caravans were sent from 1577 to 1580, with gifts for the authorities of Mecca and Medina.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] During this period, Akbar financed the pilgrimages of many poor Muslims from the Mughal Empire and also funded the foundations of the Qadiriyya Sufi Order's dervish lodge in the Hijaz.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] Akbar's attempts to build Mughal presence in Mecca and Medina reassured the local Sharifs of the Mughal Empire's ability to provide financial support, lessening their dependency upon Ottoman bounties.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] Mughal-Ottoman trade also flourished during this period; merchants loyal to Akbar are known to have reached Aleppo after journeying upriver through the port of Basra.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] The imperial Mughal entourage stayed in Mecca and Medina for nearly four years and attended the Hajj four times.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] In 1582, the Ottoman authorities forced them to return to India.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] Historian Naimur Rahman Farooqi has suggested that their expulsion may explain why Akbar broke relations with the Hijaz and stopped sending Hajj caravans after 1581.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] According to some accounts, Akbar expressed a desire to form an alliance with the Portuguese against the Ottomans, but nothing came of the idea.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] Before Akbar's rule, the Safavids and the Mughals had a long history of diplomatic relations.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] The Safavid ruler Tahmasp I provided refuge to Humayun when he was forced to flee the Indian subcontinent following his defeat by Sher Shah Suri.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] However, the Safavids differed from the Sunni Mughals in following the Shia branch of Islam.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] One of the longest-standing disputes between the Safavids and the Mughals pertained to control of the city of Kandahar in the Hindu Kush region, which formed the border between the two empires.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] Military strategists of the time considered the region to be militarily significant due to its geography.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] The city, which was administered by Bairam Khan at the time of Akbar's accession, was invaded and captured by the Persian ruler Soltan Hosayn Mirza, a cousin of Tahmasp I, in 1558.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] Shortly afterwards, Akbar's army completed its annexation of Kabul, and to further secure the north-western boundaries of his empire, it proceeded to Kandahar.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] The city capitulated without resistance on 18 April 1595, and the ruler Mozaffar-Hosayn Mirza joined Akbar's court.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] Subsequent to this, Bairam Khan sent an envoy to the court of Tahmasp I in an effort to maintain peaceful relations with the Safavids.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] This gesture was reciprocated and a cordial relationship prevailed between the two empires during the remainder of the first two decades of Akbar's reign.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] The death of Tahmasp I in 1576 resulted in civil war and instability in the Safavid empire, and diplomatic relations between the two empires ceased for more than a decade.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] They were restored only in 1587 following the accession of Shah Abbas to the Safavid throne.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] Diplomatic relations continued to be maintained between the Safavid and Mughal courts until the end of Akbar's reign.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] Kandahar remained in Mughal possession, and the Hindu Kush was the empire's western frontier for several decades until Shah Jahan's expedition into Badakhshan in 1646.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] Vincent Arthur Smith has observed that the merchant Mildenhall was employed in 1600 to bear a letter from Queen Elizabeth to Akbar requesting liberty to trade in his dominions on terms as good as those enjoyed by the Portuguese.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p01] Akbar was also visited by the French explorer Pierre Malherbe.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p02] Akbar and other members of his family, are believed to have been Sunni Hanafi Muslims. except his mother who was a Persian Shia His early days were spent in the backdrop of an atmosphere in which liberal sentiments were encouraged and religious narrow-mindedness was frowned upon.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p02] From the 15th century, a number of rulers in various parts of the country adopted a more liberal policy of religious tolerance, attempting to foster communal harmony between Hindus and Muslims.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p02] These sentiments were earlier encouraged by the teachings of popular saints like Guru Nanak, Kabir, and Chaitanya, and the verses of the Persian poet Hafez, which advocated human sympathy and a liberal outlook.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p02] The Timurid ethos of religious tolerance persisted from the times of Timur to Humayun, and influenced Akbar's policy of tolerance in matters of religion.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p02] Akbar's childhood tutors, including two Irani Shias, were largely above sectarian prejudices, and made a significant contribution to Akbar's later inclination towards religious tolerance.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p02] Akbar sponsored religious debates between different Muslim groups (Sunni, Shia, Ismaili, and Sufis), Parsis, Hindus (Shaivite and Vaishnava), Sikhs, Jains, Jews, Jesuits, and Materialists.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p02] He was also partial to Sufism; he proclaimed that "the wisdom of Vedanta is the wisdom of Sufism".
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p02] During the early part of his reign, Akbar adopted an attitude of suppression towards Muslim sects that were condemned by the orthodoxy as heretical.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p02] In 1567, on the advice of Shaikh Abdu'n Nabi, he ordered the exhumation of Mir Murtaza Sharifi Shirazi – a Shia buried in Delhi – because of the grave's proximity to that of Amir Khusrau, arguing that a "heretic" could not be buried so close to the grave of a Sunni saint.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p02] This reflected a restrictive attitude towards the Shia, which continued to persist until the early 1570s.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p02] He suppressed Mahdavism in 1573 during his campaign in Gujarat, in the course of which the Mahdavi leader Bandagi Miyan Sheik Mustafa was arrested and brought in chains to the court for debate and released after eighteen months.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p02] Akbar was reportedly angered by acts of embezzlement by many high level Muslim clerics.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p02] As Akbar increasingly came under the influence of pantheistic Sufi mysticism from the early 1570s, his outlook shifted from orthodox Islam as traditionally professed, to a new concept of Islam that transcended the limits of Islam.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p02] During the latter half of his reign, he adopted a policy of tolerance towards the Shias and declared a prohibition on Shia-Sunni conflict, and the empire remained neutral in matters of internal sectarian conflict.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p02] To strengthen his position in dealing with the *ulema* (Muslim legal scholars), Akbar issued a *mazhar*, or declaration, that was signed by all major *ulemas* in 1579.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p02] The *mahzar* asserted that Akbar was the *Khalifa* of the age, a higher rank than that of a *Mujtahid*; in case of a difference of opinion among the Mujtahids, Akbar could select any one opinion and could also issue decrees that did not go against the *nass*.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p02] Given the prevailing Islamic sectarian conflicts in various parts of the country at that time, it is believed that the *mazhar* helped stabilise the religious situation in the empire.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p02] It also helped him eliminate the religious and political influence of the Ottoman *Khalifa* over his subjects, thus ensuring their loyalty to him.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p02] In 1580, a rebellion broke out in the eastern part of Akbar's empire, and a number of *fatwas*, declaring Akbar to be a heretic, were issued by Qazis.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p02] Akbar suppressed the rebellion and handed out severe punishments to the Qazis.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p02] Throughout his reign, Akbar was a patron of influential Muslim scholars such as Mir Ahmed Nasrallah Thattvi and Tahir Muhammad Thattvi.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p02] Akbar was deeply interested in religious and philosophical matters.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p02] An orthodox Muslim at the outset, he later came to be influenced by the Sufi mysticism that was being preached in the country at that time.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p02] He moved away from orthodoxy, appointing to his court several people with liberal religious philosophies, including Abul Fazl, Faizi, and Birbal.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p02] In 1575, he built a hall called the Ibadat Khana (*"House of Worship"*) at Fatehpur Sikri, to which he invited theologians, mystics, and selected courtiers renowned for their intellectual achievements to discuss matters of spirituality with them.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p02] These discussions, initially restricted to Muslims, were acrimonious and resulted in the participants shouting at and abusing each other.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p02] Upset by this, Akbar opened the Ibadat Khana to people of all religions as well as atheists, resulting in the scope of the discussions broadening, even extending into areas such as the validity of the Quran and the nature of God.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p02] This shocked orthodox theologians, who sought to discredit Akbar by circulating rumours of his desire to forsake Islam.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p02] Akbar's effort to evolve a meeting point among the representatives of various religions was not successful, as each of them attempted to assert the superiority of their respective religions by denouncing other religions.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p02] The debates at the Ibadat Khana grew more acrimonious and, contrary to their purpose of leading to a better understanding among religions, instead led to greater bitterness among them, resulting in the discontinuance of the debates by Akbar in 1582.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p02] Akbar's interaction with various religious theologians had convinced him that despite their differences, all religions had several good practices, which he sought to combine into a new religious movement known as Din-i-Ilahi.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p02] Virtues in Din-i-Ilahi included generosity, forgiveness, abstinence, prudence, wisdom, kindness, and piety.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p02] Celibacy was respected, chastity enforced, the slaughter of animals was discouraged, and there were no sacred scriptures or a priestly hierarchy.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p02] A leading noble of Akbar's court, Aziz Koka, wrote a letter to him from Mecca in 1594 arguing that the discipleship promoted by Akbar amounted to nothing more than a desire on Akbar's part to portray his superiority regarding religious matters.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p02] To commemorate Din-e-Ilahi, Akbar changed the name of Prayag to Allahabad (pronounced as *ilahabad*) in 1583.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p02] Some modern scholars claim that Akbar did not initiate a new religion, instead introducing what Oscar R.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p02] Gómez has called a transtheistic outlook, derived from tantric Tibetan Buddhism, and that Akbar did not use the word *Din-i-Ilahi*.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p02] Scholars have also argued that the theory that Din-i-Ilahi was a new religion is a misconception that arose because of erroneous translations of Abul Fazl's work by British historians.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p02] Athar Ali wrote that the policy of *sulh-e-kul*, which formed the essence of Din-i-Ilahi, was adopted by Akbar not merely for religious purposes, but as a part of general imperial administrative policy.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p02] This also formed the basis for Akbar's policy of religious tolerance.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p02] At the time of Akbar's death in 1605, there were no signs of discontent among his Muslim subjects, and even theologians like Abdu'l Haq accepted that close ties remained.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p02] Akbar decreed that Hindus who had been forced to convert to Islam could reconvert to Hinduism without facing the death penalty.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p02] Akbar was well-liked by Hindus, who sang religious hymns to him and his eulogies.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p02] He celebrated Diwali and allowed Brahman priests to tie jewelled strings around his wrists by way of blessing.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p02] Following his lead, many nobles took to wearing *rakhi* (protection charms).
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p02] He renounced beef and forbade the sale of all meats on certain days.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p02] His son Jahangir and grandson Shahjahan maintained many of Akbar's concessions, such as the ban on cow slaughter, having only vegetarian dishes on certain days of the week, and drinking only Ganges water.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p02] When Akbar was in Punjab, 200 miles away from the Ganges, water was sealed in large jars and transported to him.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p02] He referred to the Ganges water as the "water of immortality".
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p02] Akbar regularly held discussions with Jain scholars and was impacted by their teachings.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p02] His first encounter with Jain rituals was when he saw a procession of a Jain Shravaka named Champa after a six-month-long fast.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p02] Impressed by her power and devotion, he invited her guru, Hiravijaya, to Fatehpur Sikri.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p02] Hiravijaya accepted the invitation and travelled to the Mughal capital from Gujarat.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p02] Akbar was impressed with his scholarly approach.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p02] He held several inter-faith dialogues among philosophers of different religions.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p02] The arguments of Jains against eating meat persuaded him to become a vegetarian.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p02] Akbar also issued many imperial orders that were favourable for Jain interests, such as banning animal slaughter.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p02] Jain authors also wrote about their experience at the Mughal court in Sanskrit texts that are still largely unknown to Mughal historians.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p02] In 1584, 1592, and 1598, Akbar declared "Amari Ghosana", which prohibited animal slaughter during Paryushan and Mahavira Janma Kalyanak.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p02] He removed the jizya tax from Jain pilgrim places like Palitana.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p02] Santichandra, disciple of Suri, was sent to the Emperor, who in turn left his disciples Bhanuchandra and Siddhichandra in the court.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p02] Akbar invited Hiravijaya Suri's successor Vijayasena Suri to his court who visited him between 1593 and 1595.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p02] Akbar's religious tolerance was not followed by his son Jahangir, who later threatened Bhanuchandra.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p02] Akbar's reign was chronicled extensively by his court historian Abul Fazl in the books *Akbarnama* and *Ain-i-akbari*.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p02] Other contemporary sources of Akbar's reign include the works of Badayuni, Shaikhzada Rashidi, and Shaikh Ahmed Sirhindi.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p02] Akbar was a warrior, emperor, general, animal trainer (reputedly keeping thousands of hunting cheetahs during his reign and training many himself), and theologian.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p02] Believed to be dyslexic, he was read to every day and had a remarkable memory.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p02] He created a library of over 24,000 volumes written in Sanskrit, Urdu, Persian, Greek, Latin, Arabic, and Kashmiri; the library was staffed by many scholars, translators, artists, calligraphers, scribes, bookbinders, and readers, and he did much of the cataloguing himself.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p02] Akbar was said to have been a wise emperor and a sound judge of character.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p02] His son and heir, Jahangir, wrote effusive praise of Akbar's character in his memoirs, and dozens of anecdotes to illustrate his virtues.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p02] According to Jahangir, Akbar was "of the hue of wheat; his eyes and eyebrows were black, and his complexion rather dark than fair".
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p02] Akbar was not tall, but powerfully built and very agile.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p02] He was also noted for various acts of courage.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p02] One such incident occurred on his way back from Malwa to Agra when Akbar was 19 years old.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p02] Akbar rode alone in advance of his escort and was confronted by a tigress who, along with her cubs, came out from the shrubbery across his path.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p02] When the tigress charged the emperor, he was alleged to have dispatched the animal with his sword in a solitary blow.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p02] His approaching attendants found the emperor standing quietly by the side of the dead animal.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p02] Abul Fazl, as well as Akbar's critic Badayuni, described him as having a commanding personality.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p02] He was notable for his command in battle, and, "like Alexander of Macedon, was always ready to risk his life, regardless of political consequences".
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p02] He often plunged on his horse into flooded rivers during the rainy seasons and safely crossed them.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p02] He rarely indulged in cruelty and is said to have been affectionate towards his relatives.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p02] He pardoned his brother Hakim, who had rebelled.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p02] On rare occasions, he dealt cruelly with offenders, such as his maternal uncle Muazzam and his foster-brother Adham Khan, who was twice defenestrated for drawing Akbar's wrath.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p02] To defend his stance that speech arose from hearing, he carried out a language deprivation experiment, and had children raised in isolation, not allowed to be spoken to, and pointed out that as they grew older, they remained mute.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p02] During Akbar's reign, the ongoing process of inter-religious discourse and syncretism resulted in a series of religious attributions to him in terms of positions of assimilation, doubt, or uncertainty, which he either assisted himself or left unchallenged.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p02] Such hagiographical accounts of Akbar traversed a wide range of denominational and sectarian spaces, including several accounts by Parsis, Jains, and Jesuit missionaries, apart from contemporary accounts by Brahminical and Muslim orthodoxy.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p02] Existing sects and denominations, as well as various religious figures who represented popular worship felt they had a claim to him.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p02] The diversity of these accounts is attributed to the fact that his reign resulted in the formation of a flexible centralised state accompanied by personal authority and cultural heterogeneity.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p02] The *Akbarnāma* (Persian: اکبر نامہ), which literally means *Book of Akbar*, is an official biographical account of Akbar written in Persian.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p02] It includes vivid and detailed descriptions of his life and times.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p02] The work was commissioned by Akbar, and written by Abul Fazl, one of the *Nine Jewels* (Hindi: Navaratnas) of Akbar's royal court.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p02] The book reportedly took seven years to complete and the original manuscripts contained a number of paintings supporting the texts.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p02] The paintings are in the Mughal school of painting, and included works of masters of the imperial workshop, including Basawan, whose use of portraiture in its illustrations was an innovation in Indian art.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p02] Akbar's first wife and one of the chief consorts was his cousin, Princess Ruqaiya Sultan Begum, the only daughter of his paternal uncle, Prince Hindal Mirza, and his wife Sultanam Begum.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p02] In 1551, Hindal Mirza died fighting in a battle against Kamran Mirza's forces.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p02] Hindal's daughter Ruqaiya married Akbar about the time of his first appointment, at age nine, as governor of Ghazni Province.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p02] Akbar was also given the command of his uncle's army.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p02] Akbar's marriage with Ruqaiya was solemnised near Jalandhar, Punjab, when both of them were 14 years old.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p02] She died childless in January 1626 and was buried next to her father's grave.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p02] His second wife was the daughter of Abdullah Khan Mughal.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p02] The marriage took place in 1557 during the Siege of Mankot.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p02] Bairam Khan did not approve of this marriage because Abdullah's sister was married to Akbar's uncle, Prince Kamran Mirza, and so he regarded Abdullah as a partisan of Kamran.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p02] Bairam Khan opposed the match until Nasir-al-Mulk persuaded him that he could not oppose it.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p02] Nasir-al-Mulk organised a joyful gathering and a grand feast.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p02] His third wife and one of his three chief consorts was his cousin, Salima Sultan Begum, the daughter of Nur-ud-din Muhammad Mirza and his wife Gulrukh Begum, also known as Gulrang, the daughter of Emperor Babur.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p02] She was at first betrothed to Bairam Khan by Humayun.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p02] After Bairam Khan died in 1561, Akbar married her in the same year.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p02] She was the foster mother of Akbar's second son, Murad Mirza.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p02] She was a poet and actively played a role in the politics of the Mughal court during Akbar's and Jahangir's reigns.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p02] She is regarded as the senior-most wife of Akbar.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p02] Akbar's fourth and favourite wife, Mariam-uz-Zamani, commonly known by the misnomer Jodha Bai, was the daughter of the ruler of Amer, Raja Bharmal, and by birth, was of Rajput caste.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p02] They got married on 6 February 1562 at the imperial military camp in Sambhar, Rajasthan, near Amer, and became one of Akbar's chief consorts.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p02] She gradually became one of his influential wives and was said to possess uncommon beauty.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p02] Shortly after marriage, Akbar named her 'Wali Nimat Begum' (Blessings/Gift of God).
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p02] Their marriage took place when Akbar was on his way back from Ajmer after offering prayers to the tomb of Moinuddin Chishti.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p02] Raja Bharmal had conveyed to Akbar that he was being harassed by his brother-in-law Sharif-ud-din Mirza (the Mughal *hakim* of Mewat).
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p02] Akbar insisted that the Raja should submit to him personally; it was also suggested that his daughter should be married to him as a sign of complete submission.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p02] Her marriage is considered one of the most important events in the history of the Mughal Empire.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p02] She became his first wife to have given birth to Akbar's sons.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p02] In 1564, she delivered twins named Mirza Hassan and Mirza Hussain and in 1569, she was honoured with the title of 'Mariam-uz-Zamani' after giving birth to their third and first surviving son, Prince Salim (the future emperor Jahangir), the heir to the throne.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p02] She was also the foster mother of Akbar's favourite son, Daniyal Mirza.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p02] She commanded a high rank in the imperial harem and was a recipient of many privileges.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p02] She was an intellectual woman who held a considerable influence in Akbar's court and is known as the prime driving force for Akbar's promotion of secularism and religious neutrality.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p02] She was also a great female patron of the architecture of her time.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p02] She died on 19 May 1623 in Agra and was buried in a grave close to her husband, Akbar, in Sikandra, Agra.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p02] In 1562, Akbar married the former wife of Abdul Wasi, the son of Shaikh Bada, lord of Agra.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p02] Akbar was enamored with her beauty and ordered Abdul Wasi to divorce her.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p02] Another of his wives was Gauhar-un-Nissa Begum, the daughter of Shaikh Muhammad Bakhtiyar and the sister of Shaikh Jamal Bakhtiyar.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p02] Their dynasty was called Din Laqab they lived in Chandwar and Jalesar near Agra.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p02] He married the daughter of Jagmal Rathore, son of Rao Viramde of Merta in 1562.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p02] His next marriage took place in 1564 to the daughter of Miran Mubarak Shah, the ruler of Khandesh.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p02] In 1564, he sent presents to the court with a request that his daughter be married to Akbar.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p02] Miran's request acceded and an order was issued.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p02] Itimad Khan was sent with Miran's ambassadors.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p02] Miran welcomed Itimad with honour and despatched his daughter with him.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p02] A large number of nobles accompanied her.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p02] The marriage took place in September 1564 when she reached Akbar's court.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p02] As a dowry, Mubarak Shah ceded Bijagarh and Handia to his imperial son-in-law.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p02] He married another Rajput princess in 1570, Raj Kunwari, daughter of Kanha, the brother of Rai Kalyan Mal, the ruler of Bikanir.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p02] The marriage took place in 1570 when Akbar came to this part of the country.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p02] Kalyan made a homage to Akbar and requested that his brother's daughter be married to him.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p02] Akbar accepted his proposal, and the marriage was arranged.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p02] He also married Bhanmati, daughter of Bhim Raj, another brother of Rai Kalyan Mal.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p02] He also married Nathi Bai, daughter of Rawal Har Rai, the ruler of Jaisalmer in 1570.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p02] Rawal had sent a request that his daughter be married to Akbar.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p02] Raja Bhagwan Das was despatched on this service.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p02] The marriage ceremony took place after Akbar's return from Nagor.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p02] She was the mother of Princess Mahi Begum, who died on 8 April 1577.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p02] In 1570, Narhardas, a grandson of Rao Viramde of Merta, married his sister, Puram Bai, to Akbar in return for Akbar's support of Keshodas's claims on Merta.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p02] Another of his wives was Bhakkari Begum, the daughter of Sultan Mahmud of Bhakkar.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p02] On 2 July 1572, Akbar's envoy Itimad Khan reached Mahmud's court to escort his daughter to Akbar.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p02] Itimad Khan brought a dress, a bejewelled scimitar belt, a horse with a saddle and reins, and four elephants.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p02] Mahmud celebrated the occasion by holding extravagant feasts for fifteen days.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p02] On the day of the wedding, the ulema, saints, and nobles were honoured with rewards.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p02] Mahmud offered 30,000 rupees in cash and kind to Itimad Khan and sent his daughter with a grand dowry and an entourage.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p02] She came to Ajmer and waited upon Akbar.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p02] The gifts of Sultan Mahmud, carried by the delegation, were presented to the ladies of the imperial harem.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p02] His eleventh wife was Qasima Banu Begum, the daughter of Arab Shah.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p02] A fest was held, at which the high officers and other pillars of the state were present.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p02] In 1577, the Rawal Askaran of Dungarpur State requested that his daughter be married to Akbar.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p02] Rai Loukaran and Rajah Birbar, servants of the Rajah, were sent from Dihalpur to do the honour of conveying his daughter.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p02] The two delivered her to Akbar's court where the marriage took place on 12 July 1577.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p02] She was the mother of Princess Shakr-un-Nissa Begum, and Princess Aram Banu Begum born on 22 December 1584.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p02] His next wife was the daughter of Shams Chak, a Kashmiri.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p02] The marriage took place on 3 November 1592.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p02] In 1593, he married the daughter of Qazi Isa and the cousin of Najib Khan.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p02] Najib told Akbar that his uncle had made his daughter a present for him.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p02] Akbar accepted his representation and on 3 July 1593, he visited Najib Khan's house and married Qazi Isa's daughter.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p02] At some point, Akbar took into his harem Rukmavati, a daughter Maldeo Rathore, Rao of Marwar, by his mistress, Tipu Gudi.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p02] This was a *dolo* union as opposed to a formal marriage, representing the bride's lower status in her father's household, and serving as an expression of vassalage to an overlord.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p02] The dating of this event is not recorded.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p02] On 3 October 1605, Akbar fell ill from an attack of dysentery, from which he never recovered.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p02] He is believed to have died on 26 October 1605.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p02] He was buried at his mausoleum in Sikandra, Agra, which lies a kilometer next to the tomb of Mariam-uz-Zamani, his favourite consort.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p02] Akbar firmly entrenched the authority of the Mughal Empire in India and beyond, after it had been threatened by the Afghans during his father's reign, establishing its military and diplomatic superiority.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p02] Folk tales revolving around him and Birbal, one of his *navaratnas*, are popular in India.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p02] He and his Hindu wife, Mariam-uz-Zamani are widely popular, as the latter is believed to have been the prime inspiration and driving force for Akbar's promotion of secularism and universal benevolence.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p02] Citing Akbar's melding of the disparate "fiefdoms" of India into the Mughal Empire, as well as the lasting legacy of "pluralism and tolerance" that "underlies the values of the modern republic of India", *Time* included him in its list of top 25 world leaders.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p02] Akbar's legacy is largely negative in Pakistan.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p02] Historian Mubarak Ali, in a study of the image of Akbar in Pakistani textbooks, has observed that Akbar "is conveniently ignored and not mentioned in any school textbook from class one to matriculation", as opposed to the omnipresence of emperor Aurangzeb.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p02] He quotes historian Ishtiaq Hussain Qureshi, who said that, due to his religious tolerance, "Akbar had so weakened Islam through his policies that it could not be restored to its dominant position in the affairs".
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p02] A common thread among Pakistani historians is criticism of Akbar's Rajput policy.
[src:gunpowder/akbar-p02] Ali has stated that "Akbar is criticized for bringing Muslims and Hindus together as one nation and putting the separate identity of the Muslims in danger.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] Alauddin was a nephew and a son-in-law of his predecessor Jalaluddin.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] When Jalaluddin became the Sultan of Delhi after deposing the Mamluks, Alauddin was given the position of *Amir-i-Tuzuk* (equivalent to master of ceremonies).
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] After suppressing a revolt against Jalaluddin, Alauddin obtained the governorship of Kara in 1291, and the governorship of Awadh in 1296, after a profitable raid on Bhilsa.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] In 1296, Alauddin raided Devagiri, and used the acquired loot to stage a successful revolt against Jalaluddin.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] After killing Jalaluddin, he consolidated his power in Delhi, and subjugated Jalaluddin's sons in Multan.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] Over the next few years, Alauddin successfully fended off the Mongol invasions from the Chagatai Khanate, at Jaran-Manjur (1297–1298), Sivistan (1298), Kili (1299), Delhi (1303), and Amroha (1305).
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] In 1306, his forces achieved a decisive victory against the Mongols near the Ravi riverbank, and later ransacked the Mongol territories in present-day Afghanistan.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] The military commanders that successfully led his army against the Mongols include Zafar Khan, Ulugh Khan, and Alauddin's slave-general Malik Kafur.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] These victories ended several Rajput and other Hindu dynasties, including the Paramaras, the Vaghelas, the Chahamanas of Ranastambhapura and Jalore, the Rawal branch of the Guhilas, and possibly the Yajvapalas.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] His slave-general Malik Kafur led multiple campaigns to the south of the Vindhyas, obtaining a considerable amount of wealth from Devagiri (1308), Warangal (1310) and Dwarasamudra (1311).
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] These victories forced the Yadava king Ramachandra, the Kakatiya king Prataparudra, and the Hoysala king Ballala III to become Alauddin's tributaries.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] Kafur also raided the Pandya kingdom (1311), obtaining much treasure, elephants, and horses.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] During the last years of his life, Alauddin had an illness and relied on Malik Kafur to handle the administration.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] After his death in 1316, Malik Kafur appointed Shihabuddin, son of Alauddin and his Hindu wife Jhatyapali, as a puppet monarch.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] Alauddin's elder son Qutbuddin Mubarak Shah seized power shortly after his death.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] Contemporary chroniclers did not write much about Alauddin's childhood.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] According to the 16th/17th-century chronicler Haji-ud-Dabir, Alauddin was 34 years old when he started his march to Ranthambore (1300–1301).
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] Assuming this is correct, Alauddin's birth can be dated to 1266–1267.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] He was the eldest son of Shihabuddin Mas'ud, who was the elder brother of the Khalji dynasty's founder Sultan Jalaluddin.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] He had three brothers: Almas Beg (later Ulugh Khan), Qutlugh Tigin, and Muhammad.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] Alauddin was brought up by Jalaluddin after Shihabuddin's death.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] Both Alauddin and his younger brother Almas Beg married Jalaluddin's daughters.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] After Jalaluddin became the Sultan of Delhi, Alauddin was appointed as *Amir-i-Tuzuk* (equivalent to Master of the Ceremonies), while Almas Beg was given the post of *Akhur-Beg* (equivalent to Master of the Horse).
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] Alauddin married Jalaluddin's daughter, Malika-i-Jahan, long before the Khalji revolution of 1290.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] The marriage, however, was not a happy one.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] Having suddenly become a princess after Jalaluddin's rise as a monarch, she was very arrogant and tried to dominate Alauddin.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] According to Haji-ud-Dabir, Alauddin married a second woman, named Mahru, who was the sister of Malik Sanjar alias Alp Khan.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] Malika-i-Jahan was greatly infuriated by her husband taking a second wife.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] According to Dabir, this was the main cause of the misunderstanding between Alauddin and his first wife.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] Once, while Alauddin and Mahru were together in a garden, Jalaluddin's daughter attacked Mahru out of jealousy.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] The incident was reported to Jalaluddin, but the Sultan did not take any action against Alauddin.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] Alauddin was not on good terms with his mother-in-law either, who wielded great influence over the Sultan.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] According to the 16th-century historian Firishta, she warned Jalaluddin that Alauddin was planning to set up an independent kingdom in a remote part of the country.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] She closely monitored Alauddin and encouraged her daughter's arrogant behavior toward him.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] In 1291, Alauddin played an important role in crushing a revolt by the governor of Kara Malik Chajju.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] Jalaluddin rewarded Alauddin by appointing him as the new governor of Kara in 1291.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] Malik Chajju's former *Amirs* (subordinate nobles) at Kara considered Jalaluddin as a weak and ineffective ruler and instigated Alauddin to usurp the throne of Delhi.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] This, combined with his unhappy domestic life, made Alauddin determined to dethrone Jalaluddin.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] While instigating Alauddin to revolt against Jalaluddin, Malik Chajju's supporters emphasized that he needed a lot of money to raise a large army and stage a successful coup: Malik Chajju's revolt had failed for want of resources.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] To finance his plan to dethrone Jalaluddin, Alauddin decided to raid the neighboring Hindu kingdoms.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] In 1293, he raided Bhilsa, a wealthy town in the Paramara kingdom of Malwa, which had been weakened by multiple invasions.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] At Bhilsa, he learned of the immense wealth of the southern Yadava kingdom in the Deccan region, as well as about the routes leading to their capital Devagiri.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] Therefore, he shrewdly surrendered the loot from Bhilsa to Jalaluddin to win Sultan's confidence, while withholding the information on the Yadava kingdom.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] A pleased Jalaluddin gave him the office of *Ariz-i Mamalik* (Minister of War), and also made him the governor of Awadh.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] In addition, the Sultan granted Alauddin's request to use the revenue surplus for hiring additional troops.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] After years of planning and preparation, Alauddin successfully raided Devagiri in 1296.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] He left Devagiri with a huge amount of wealth, including precious metals, jewels, silk products, elephants, horses, and slaves.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] When the news of Alauddin's success reached Jalaluddin, the Sultan came to Gwalior, hoping that Alauddin would present the loot to him there.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] However, Alauddin marched directly to Kara with all the wealth.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] Jalaluddin's advisors such as Ahmad Chap recommended intercepting Alauddin at Chanderi, but Jalaluddin had faith in his nephew.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] He returned to Delhi, believing that Alauddin would carry the wealth from Kara to Delhi.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] After reaching Kara, Alauddin sent a letter of apology to the Sultan and expressed concern that his enemies may have poisoned Sultan's mind against him during his absence.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] He requested a letter of pardon signed by the Sultan, which the Sultan immediately despatched through messengers.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] At Kara, Jalaluddin's messengers learned of Alauddin's military strength and of his plans to dethrone the Sultan.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] However, Alauddin detained them and prevented them from communicating with the Sultan.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] Meanwhile, Alauddin's younger brother Almas Beg (later Ulugh Khan), who was married to a daughter of Jalaluddin, assured the Sultan of Alauddin's loyalty.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] He convinced Jalaluddin to visit Kara and meet Alauddin, saying that Alauddin would commit suicide out of guilt if the Sultan did not pardon him personally.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] A gullible Jalaluddin set out for Kara with his army.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] After reaching close to Kara, he directed Ahmad Chap to take his main army to Kara by land route, while he himself decided to cross the Ganges river with a smaller body of around 1,000 soldiers.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] On 20 July 1296, Alauddin had Jalaluddin killed, after pretending to greet the Sultan, and declaring himself the new king.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] Jalaluddin's companions were also killed, while Ahmad Chap's army retreated to Delhi.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] Alauddin, known as Ali Gurshasp until his ascension in July 1296, was formally proclaimed as the new king with the title *Alauddunya wad Din Muhammad Shah-us Sultan* at Kara.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] Meanwhile, the head of Jalaluddin was paraded on a spear in his camp before being sent to Awadh.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] Over the next two days, Alauddin formed a provisional government at Kara.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] He promoted the existing *Amirs* to the rank of *Maliks*, and appointed his close friends as the new *Amirs*.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] At that time, there were heavy rains, and the Ganga and the Yamuna rivers were flooded.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] But Alauddin made preparations for a march to Delhi, and ordered his officers to recruit as many soldiers as possible, without fitness tests or background checks.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] His objective was to cause a change in the general political opinion, by portraying himself as someone with huge public support.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] To portray himself as a generous king, he ordered 5 manns of gold pieces to be shot from a *manjaniq* (catapult) at a crowd in Kara.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] One section of his army, led by himself and Nusrat Khan, marched to Delhi via Badaun and Baran (modern Bulandshahr).
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] The other section, led by Zafar Khan, marched to Delhi via Koil (modern Aligarh).
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] As Alauddin marched to Delhi, the news spread in towns and villages that he was recruiting soldiers while distributing gold.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] Many people, from both military and non-military backgrounds, joined him.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] By the time he reached Badaun, he had a 56,000-strong cavalry and a 60,000-strong infantry.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] At Baran, Alauddin was joined by seven powerful Jalaluddin nobles who had earlier opposed him.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] These nobles were Tajul Mulk Kuchi, Malik Abaji Akhur-bek, Malik Amir Ali Diwana, Malik Usman Amir-akhur, Malik Amir Khan, Malik Umar Surkha, and Malik Hiranmar.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] Alauddin gave each of them 30 to 50 *mann*s of gold, and each of their soldiers 300 silver *tanka*s (hammered coins).
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] Alauddin's march to Delhi was interrupted by the flooding of the Yamuna river.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] Meanwhile, in Delhi, Jalaluddin's widow *Malka-i-Jahan* appointed her youngest son Qadr Khan as the new king with the title Ruknuddin Ibrahim, without consulting the nobles.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] This irked Arkali Khan, her elder son and the governor of Multan.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] When *Malika-i-Jahan* heard that Jalaluddin's nobles had joined Alauddin, she apologized to Arkali and offered him the throne, requesting him to march from Multan to Delhi.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] However, Arkali refused to come to her aid.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] Alauddin resumed his march to Delhi in the second week of October 1296, when the Yamuna river subsided.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] When he reached Siri, Ruknuddin led an army against him.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] However, a section of Ruknuddin's army defected to Alauddin at midnight.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] A dejected Ruknuddin then retreated and escaped to Multan with his mother and the loyal nobles.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] Alauddin then entered the city, where a number of nobles and officials accepted his authority.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] On 21 October 1296, Alauddin was formally proclaimed as the Sultan in Delhi.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] Initially, Alauddin consolidated power by making generous grants and endowments and appointing many people to government positions.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] He balanced the power between the officers appointed by the Mamluks, the ones appointed by Jalaluddin and his own appointees.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] He also increased the strength of the Sultanate's army, and gifted every soldier the salary of a year and a half in cash.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] Of Alauddin's first year as the Sultan, chronicler Ziauddin Barani wrote that it was the happiest year that the people of Delhi had ever seen.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] At this time, Alauddin could not exercise his authority over all of Jalaluddin's former territories.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] In the Punjab region, his authority was limited to the areas east of the Ravi river.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] The region beyond Lahore suffered from Mongol raids and Khokhar rebellions.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] Multan was controlled by Jalaluddin's son Arkali, who harbored the fugitives from Delhi.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] In November 1296, Alauddin sent an army led by Ulugh Khan and Zafar Khan to conquer Multan.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] On his orders, Nusrat Khan arrested, blinded, and/or killed the surviving members of Jalaluddin's family.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] Shortly after the conquest of Multan, Alauddin appointed Nusrat Khan as his *wazir* (prime minister).
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] Having strengthened his control over Delhi, the Sultan started eliminating the officers that were not his own appointees.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] In 1297, the aristocrats (*maliks*), who had deserted Jalaluddin's family to join Alauddin, were arrested, blinded or killed.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] All their property, including the money earlier given to them by Alauddin, was confiscated.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] As a result of these confiscations, Nusrat Khan obtained a huge amount of cash for the royal treasury.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] Only three *malik*s from Jalaluddin's time were spared: Malik Qutbuddin Alavi, Malik Nasiruddin Rana, and Malik Amir Jamal Khalji.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] The rest of the older aristocrats were replaced with the new nobles, who were extremely loyal to Alauddin.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] Meanwhile, Ala-ul Mulk, who was Alauddin's governor at Kara, came to Delhi with all the officers, elephants, and wealth that Alauddin had left at Kara.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] Alauddin appointed Ala-ul Mulk as the kotwal of Delhi and placed all the non-Turkic municipal employees under his charge.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] Since Ala-ul Mulk had become very obese, the governorship of Kara was entrusted to Nusrat Khan, who had become unpopular in Delhi because of the confiscations.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] In the winter of 1297, the Mongols led by a noyan of the Chagatai Khanate raided Punjab, advancing as far as Kasur.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] Alauddin's forces, led by Ulugh Khan, defeated the Mongols on 6 February 1298.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] According to Amir Khusrow, 20,000 Mongols were killed in the battle, and many more were killed in Delhi after being brought there as prisoners.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] In 1298–99, another Mongol army (possibly Neguderi fugitives) invaded Sindh, and occupied the fort of Sivistan.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] This time, Alauddin's general Zafar Khan defeated the invaders and recaptured the fort.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] In early 1299, Alauddin sent Ulugh Khan and Nusrat Khan to invade Gujarat, where the Vaghela king Karna offered a weak resistance.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] Alauddin's army plundered several towns including Somnath, where it desecrated the famous Hindu temple.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] The Delhi army also captured several people, including the Vaghela queen Kamala Devi and slave Malik Kafur, who later led Alauddin's southern campaigns.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] During the army's return journey to Delhi, some of its Mongol soldiers staged an unsuccessful mutiny near Jalore, after the generals forcibly tried to extract a share of loot (*khums*) from them.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] Alauddin's administration meted out brutal punishments to the mutineers' families in Delhi, including killings of children in front of their mothers.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] According to Ziauddin Barani, the practice of punishing wives and children for the crimes of men started with this incident in Delhi.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] In 1299, the Chagatai ruler Duwa sent a Mongol force led by Qutlugh Khwaja to conquer Delhi.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] In the ensuing Battle of Kili, Alauddin personally led the Delhi forces, but his general Zafar Khan attacked the Mongols without waiting for his orders.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] Although Zafar Khan managed to inflict heavy casualties on the invaders, he and other soldiers in his unit were killed in the battle.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] Qutlugh Khwaja was also seriously wounded, forcing the Mongols to retreat, Qutlugh Khwaja later died on the way while retreating.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] Around the same time, Alauddin turned his attention towards the present-day state of Rajasthan to subdue the Rajput kingdoms for a secure base to Gujarat and Malwa and for further expeditions in the South.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] In 1299 CE, Alauddin besieged the fortress of Jaisalmer ruled by Bhatis at the time under Jait Singh I.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] Following a long siege and due to the dearth of food and resources, eventually, the besieged Rajputs under the command of Mularaja performed Saka where the women committed Jauhar and the men fought until death.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] Thus, Alauddin successfully penetrated into territories of the Bhattis.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] After the conquest of Jaisalmer, it remained under the Khalji's for few more years.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] In 1301, Alauddin ordered Ulugh Khan and Nusrat Khan to invade Ranthambore, whose king Hammiradeva had granted asylum to the leaders of the mutiny near Jalore.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] After Nusrat Khan was killed during the siege, Alauddin personally took charge of the siege operations, and conquered the fort in July 1301.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] During the Ranthambore campaign, Alauddin faced three unsuccessful rebellions.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] To suppress any future rebellions, he set up an intelligence and surveillance system, instituted a total prohibition in Delhi, established laws to prevent his nobles from networking with each other, and confiscated wealth from the general public.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] In the winter of 1302–1303, Alauddin dispatched an army to ransack the Kakatiya capital Warangal.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] Meanwhile, he himself led another army to conquer Chittor, the capital of the Guhila kingdom ruled by Ratnasimha.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] Alauddin captured Chittor after an eight-month long siege.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] According to his courtier Amir Khusrau, he ordered a massacre of 30,000 local Hindus after this conquest.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] Some later legends state that Alauddin invaded Chittor to capture Ratnasimha's beautiful queen Padmini, but most modern historians have rejected the authenticity of these legends.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] While the imperial armies were busy in Chittor and Warangal campaigns, the Mongols launched another invasion of Delhi around August 1303.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] Alauddin managed to reach Delhi before the invaders, but did not have enough time to prepare for a strong defence.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] Meanwhile, the Warangal campaign was unsuccessful (because of heavy rains according to Ziauddin Barani), and the army had lost several men and its baggage.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] Neither this army, nor the reinforcements sent by Alauddin's provincial governors could enter the city because of the blockades set up by the Mongols.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] Under these difficult circumstances, Alauddin took shelter in a heavily guarded camp at the under-construction Siri Fort.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] The Mongols engaged his forces in some minor conflicts, but neither army achieved a decisive victory.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] The invaders ransacked Delhi and its neighbourhoods, but ultimately decided to retreat after being unable to breach Siri.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] The Mongol invasion of 1303 was one of the most serious invasions of India, and prompted Alauddin to take several steps to prevent its repeat.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] He strengthened the forts and the military presence along the Mongol routes to India.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] He also implemented a series of economic reforms to ensure sufficient revenue inflows for maintaining a strong army.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] In 1304, Alauddin appears to have ordered a second invasion of Gujarat, which resulted in the annexation of the Vaghela kingdom to the Delhi Sultanate.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] In 1305, he launched an invasion of Malwa in central India, which resulted in the defeat and death of the Paramara king Mahalakadeva.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] The Yajvapala dynasty, which ruled the region to the north-east of Malwa, also appears to have fallen to Alauddin's invasion.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] In December 1305, the Mongols invaded India again.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] Instead of attacking the heavily guarded city of Delhi, the invaders proceeded south-east to the Gangetic plains along the Himalayan foothills.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] Alauddin's 30,000-strong cavalry, led by Malik Nayak, defeated the Mongols at the Battle of Amroha.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] Many Mongols were taken captive and killed; the 16th-century historian Firishta claims that the heads (*sir*) of 8,000 Mongols were used to build the Siri Fort commissioned by Alauddin.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] In 1306, another Mongol army sent by Duwa advanced up to the Ravi River, ransacking the territories along the way.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] Alauddin's forces, led by Malik Kafur, decisively defeated the Mongols.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] Duwa died next year, and after that the Mongols did not launch any further expeditions to India during Alauddin's reign.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] On the contrary, Alauddin's Dipalpur governor Malik Tughluq regularly raided the Mongol territories located in present-day Afghanistan.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] Around 1308, Alauddin sent Malik Kafur to invade Devagiri, whose king Ramachandra had discontinued the tribute payments promised in 1296, and had granted asylum to the Vaghela king Karna at Baglana.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] Kafur was supported by Alauddin's Gujarat governor Alp Khan, whose forces invaded Baglana, and captured Karna's daughter Devaladevi (later married to Alauddin's son Khizr Khan).
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] At Devagiri, Kafur achieved an easy victory, and Ramachandra agreed to become a lifelong vassal of Alauddin.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] Meanwhile, a section of Alauddin's army had been besieging the fort of Siwana in Marwar region unsuccessfully for several years.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] In August–September 1308, Alauddin personally took charge of the siege operations in Siwana.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] The Delhi army conquered the fort in the Siege of Siwana, and the defending ruler Sitaladeva was killed in November 1308.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] The plunder obtained from Devagiri prompted Alauddin to plan an invasion of the other southern kingdoms, which had accumulated a huge amount of wealth, having been shielded from the foreign armies that had ransacked northern India.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] In late 1309, he sent Malik Kafur to ransack the Kakatiya capital Warangal.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] Helped by Ramachandra of Devagiri, Kafur entered the Kakatiya territory in January 1310, ransacking towns and villages on his way to Warangal.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] After a month-long siege of Warangal, the Kakatiya king Prataparudra agreed to become a tributary of Alauddin, and surrendered a large amount of wealth (possibly including the Koh-i-Noor diamond) to the invaders.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] Meanwhile, after conquering Siwana, Alauddin had ordered his generals to subjugate other parts of Marwar, before returning to Delhi.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] The raids of his generals in Marwar led to their confrontations with Kanhadadeva, the Chahamana ruler of Jalore.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] In 1311, Alauddin's general Malik Kamaluddin Gurg captured the Jalore fort after defeating and killing Kanhadadeva.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] During the siege of Warangal, Malik Kafur had learned about the wealth of the Hoysala and Pandya kingdoms located further south.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] After returning to Delhi, he took Alauddin's permission to lead an expedition there.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] Kafur started his march from Delhi in November 1310, and crossed Deccan in early 1311, supported by Alauddin's tributaries Ramachandra and Prataparudra.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] At this time, the Pandya kingdom was reeling under a war of succession between the two brothers Vira and Sundara, and taking advantage of this, the Hoysala king Ballala had invaded the Pandyan territory.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] When Ballala learned about Kafur's march, he hurried back to his capital Dwarasamudra.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] However, he could not put up a strong resistance, and negotiated a truce after a short siege, agreeing to surrender his wealth and become a tributary of Alauddin.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] From Dwarasamudra, Malik Kafur marched to the Pandya kingdom, where he raided several towns reaching as far as Madurai.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] Both Vira and Sundara fled their headquarters, and thus, Kafur was unable to make them Alauddin's tributaries.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] Nevertheless, the Delhi army looted many treasures, elephants and horses.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] The Delhi chronicler Ziauddin Barani described this seizure of wealth from Dwarasamudra and the Pandya kingdom as the greatest one since the Muslim capture of Delhi.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] During this campaign, the Mongol general Abachi had conspired to ally with the Pandyas, and as a result, Alauddin ordered him to be executed in Delhi.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] This, combined with their general grievances against Alauddin, led to resentment among Mongols who had settled in India after converting to Islam.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] A section of Mongol leaders plotted to kill Alauddin, but the conspiracy was discovered by Alauddin's agents.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] Alauddin then ordered a mass massacre of Mongols in his empire, which according to Barani, resulted in the death of 20,000 or 30,000 Mongols.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] Meanwhile, in Devagiri, after Ramachandra's death, his son tried to overthrow Alauddin's suzerainty.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] Malik Kafur invaded Devagiri again in 1313, defeated him, and became the governor of Devagiri.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] Alauddin was the most powerful ruler of his dynasty.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] Unlike the previous rulers of the Delhi Sultanate, who had largely relied on the pre-existing administrative set-up, Alauddin undertook large-scale reforms.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] After facing the Mongol invasions and several rebellions, he implemented several reforms to be able to maintain a large army and to weaken those capable of organizing a revolt against him.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] Barani also attributes Alauddin's revenue reforms to the Sultan's desire to subjugate the Hindus by "depriving them of that wealth and property which fosters rebellion".
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] According to historian Satish Chandra, Alauddin's reforms were based on his conception of fear and control as the basis of good government as well as his military ambitions: the bulk of the measures were designed to centralise power in his hands and to support a large military.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] Some of Alauddin's land reforms were continued by his successors, and formed a basis of the agrarian reforms introduced by the later rulers such as Sher Shah Suri and Akbar.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] However, his other regulations, including price control, were revoked by his son Qutbuddin Mubarak Shah a few months after his death.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] The countryside and agricultural production during Alauddin's time was controlled by the village headmen, the traditional Hindu authorities.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] He viewed their haughtiness and their direct and indirect resistance as the main difficulty affecting his reign.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] He also had to face talk of conspiracies at his court.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] After some initial conspiracies and Hindu revolts in rural areas during the early period of his reign, he struck the root of the problem by introducing reforms that also aimed at ensuring support of his army and food supply to his capital.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] He took away all landed properties of his courtiers and nobles and cancelled revenue assignments which were henceforth controlled by the central authorities.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] Henceforth, "everybody was busy with earning a living so that nobody could even think of rebellion".
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] He also ordered "to supply some rules and regulations for grinding down the Hindus, and for depriving them of that wealth and property which fosters rebellion.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] Alauddin brought a large tract of fertile land under the directly governed crown territory, by eliminating iqta's, land grants and vassals in the Ganga-Yamuna Doab region.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] He imposed a 50% *kharaj* tax on the agricultural produce in a substantial part of northern India: this was the maximum amount allowed by the Hanafi school of Islam, which was dominant in Delhi at that time.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] Alauddin also eliminated the intermediary Hindu rural chiefs, and started collecting the *kharaj* directly from the cultivators.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] He did not levy any additional taxes on agriculture, and abolished the cut that the intermediaries received for collecting revenue.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] Alauddin's demand for tax proportional to land area meant that the rich and powerful villages with more land had to pay more taxes.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] He forced the rural chiefs to pay same taxes as the others, and banned them from imposing illegal taxes on the peasants.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] To prevent any rebellions, his administration deprived the rural chiefs of their wealth, horses and arms.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] By suppressing these chiefs, Alauddin projected himself as the protector of the weaker section of the rural society.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] To enforce these land and agrarian reforms, Alauddin set up a strong and efficient revenue administration system.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] His government recruited many accountants, collectors and agents.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] These officials were well-paid but were subject to severe punishment if found to be taking bribes.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] Account books were audited and even small discrepancies were punished.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] The effect was both large landowners and small-scale cultivators were fearful of missing out on paying their assessed taxes.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] Alauddin's government imposed the *jizya* tax on its non-Muslim subjects, and his Muslim subjects were obligated to contribute *zakat*.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] He also levied taxes on residences (*ghari*) and grazing (*chara'i*), which were not sanctioned by the Islamic law.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] In addition, Alauddin demanded four-fifths share of the spoils of war from his soldiers, instead of the traditional one-fifth share (*khums*).
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] Alauddin implemented price control measures for a wide variety of market goods.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] Alauddin's courtier Amir Khusrau and the 14th century writer Hamid Qalandar suggest that Alauddin introduced these changes for public welfare.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] However, Barani states that Alauddin wanted to reduce the prices so that low salaries were acceptable to his soldiers, and thus, to maintain a large army.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] In addition, Barani suggests that the Hindu traders indulged in profiteering, and Alauddin's market reforms resulted from the Sultan's desire to punish the Hindus.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] To ensure that the goods were sold at regulated prices, Alauddin appointed market supervisors and spies, and received independent reports from them.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] To prevent a black market, his administration prohibited peasants and traders from storing the grains, and established government-run granaries, where government's share of the grain was stored.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] The government also forced the transport workers to re-settle in villages at specific distances along the Yamuna river to enable rapid transport of grain to Delhi.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] Chroniclers such as Khusrau and Barani state that the prices were not allowed to increase during Alauddin's lifetime, even when the rainfall was scarce.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] The shopkeepers who violated the price control regulations or tried to circumvent them (such as, by using false weights) were given severe punishments.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] Alauddin maintained a large standing army, which included 475,000 horsemen according to the 16th-century chronicler Firishta.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] He managed to raise such a large army by paying relatively low salaries to his soldiers, and introduced market price controls to ensure that the low salaries were acceptable to his soldiers.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] Although he was opposed to granting lands to his generals and soldiers, he generously rewarded them after successful campaigns, especially those in Deccan.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] Alauddin's government maintained a descriptive roll of every soldier, and occasionally conducted strict reviews of the army to examine the horses and arms of the soldiers.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] To ensure that no horse could be presented twice or replaced by a poor-quality horse during the review, Alauddin established a system of branding the horses.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] Although Islam bans alcoholic drinks, drinking was common among the Muslim royals and nobles of the Delhi Sultanate in the 13th century, and Alauddin himself was a heavy drinker.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] As part of his measures to prevent rebellions, Alauddin imposed prohibition, because he believed that the rampant use of alcoholic drinks enabled people to assemble, lose their senses and think of rebellion.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] According to Isami, Alauddin banned alcohol, after a noble condemned him for merrymaking when his subjects were suffering from a famine.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] However, this account appears to be hearsay.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] Subsequently, Alauddin also banned other intoxicants, including cannabis.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] He also banned gambling, and excommunicated drunkards and gamblers from Delhi, along with vendors of intoxicants.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] Alauddin's administration strictly punished the violators, and ensured non-availability of alcohol not only in Delhi, but also in its surrounding areas.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] Nevertheless, alcohol continued to be illegally produced in and smuggled into Delhi.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] Sometime later, Alauddin relented, and allowed brewing and drinking in private.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] However, public distribution and drinking of wine remained prohibited.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] Alauddin also increased his level of control over the nobility.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] To prevent rebellions by the nobles, he confiscated their wealth and removed them from their bases of power.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] Even charitable lands administered by nobles were confiscated.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] Severe punishments were given for disloyalty.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] Even wives and children of soldiers rebelling for greater war spoils were imprisoned.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] An efficient spy network was set up that reached into the private households of nobles.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] Marriage alliances made between noble families had to be approved by the king.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] Alauddin banned prostitution, and ordered all existing prostitutes of Delhi to be married.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] Firishta states that he classified prostitutes into three grades, and fixed their fees accordingly.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] However, historian Kishori Saran Lal dismisses this account as inaccurate.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] Alauddin also took steps to curb adultery by ordering the male adulterer to be castrated and the female adulterer to be stoned to death.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] Alauddin banned charlatans, and ordered sorcerers (called "blood-sucking magicians" by his courtier Amir Khusrau) to be stoned to death.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] During the last years of his life, Alauddin had an illness, and became very distrustful of his officers.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] He started concentrating all the power in the hands of his family and his slaves.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] He became charmed with his slave-general Malik Kafur, who became the de facto ruler of the Sultanate after being promoted to the rank of viceroy (*Na'ib*).
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] Alauddin removed several experienced administrators, abolished the office of *wazir* (prime minister), and even executed the minister Sharaf Qa'ini.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] It appears that Malik Kafur, who considered these officers as his rivals and a threat, convinced Alauddin to carry out this purge.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] Kafur had Alauddin's eldest sons Khizr Khan and Shadi Khan blinded.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] He also convinced Alauddin to order the killing of his brother-in-law Alp Khan, an influential noble who could rival Malik Kafur's power.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] The victims allegedly hatched a conspiracy to overthrow Alauddin, but this might be Kafur's propaganda.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] Alauddin died on the night of 4 January 1316.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] Barani claims that according to "some people", Kafur murdered him.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] Towards the end of the night, Kafur brought the body of Alauddin from the Siri Place and had it buried in Alauddin's mausoleum (which had already been built before Alauddin's death).
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] The mausoleum is said to have been located outside a Jama Mosque, but neither of these structures can be identified with certainty.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] According to historian Banarsi Prasad Saksena, the ruined foundations of these two structures probably lie under one of the mounds at Siri.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] The next day, Kafur appointed Alauddin's young son Shihabuddin as a puppet monarch.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] However, Kafur was killed shortly after, and Alauddin's elder son Mubarak Khan seized the power.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] Alauddin's tomb and the *madrasa* dedicated to him exist at the back of Qutb complex, Mehrauli, in Delhi.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] Alauddin's wives included Jalaluddin's daughter, who held the title *Malika-i-Jahan*, and Alp Khan's sister Mahru.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] He also married Jhatyapali, the daughter of Hindu king Ramachandra of Devagiri, probably after the 1296 Devagiri raid, or after his 1308 conquest of Devagiri.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] Alauddin had a son with Jhatyapali, Shihabuddin Omar, who succeeded him as the next Khalji ruler.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] Alauddin also married Kamala Devi, a Hindu woman, who was originally the chief queen of Karna II, the Vaghela dynasty king of Gujarat.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] She was captured by Khalji forces during an invasion, escorted to Delhi as part of the war booty, and taken into Alauddin's harem.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] She eventually reconciled to her new life.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] According to the chronicler Firishta, sometime between 1306 and 1307, Kamala Devi requested Alauddin to secure her daughter Deval Devi from the custody of her father, Raja Karan.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] Alauddin sent an order to Raja Karan telling him to send Deval Devi immediately.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] Deval Devi was eventually brought to Delhi and lived in the royal palace with her mother.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] She was married to Khizr Khan, the eldest son of Alauddin Khalji, in 1308.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] Malik Kafur, a slave captured during the Gujarat campaign, caught the fancy of Alauddin.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] He rose rapidly in Alauddin's service, mainly because of his proven ability as military commander and wise counsellor, and eventually became the viceroy (*Na'ib*) of the Sultanate.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] A deep emotional bond developed between Alauddin and Kafur.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] According to Barani, during the last four or five years of his life, Alauddin deeply favoured Kafur, and handed over the administration to him.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] Based on Barani's description, scholars Ruth Vanita and Saleem Kidwai believe that Alauddin and Kafur were in a homosexual relationship.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] Walsh, scholar Nilanjan Sarkar and scholar Thomas Gugler also believe Alauddin and Kafur were lovers in a sexually intimate relationship.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] Given his relationship with Kafur, historians believe Alauddin may have been bisexual or even homosexual.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] Historian Banarsi Prasad Saksena believes that the closeness between the two was not sexual.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] In 1296, Alauddin constructed the Hauz-i-Alai (later Hauz-i-Khas) water reservoir, which covered an area of 70 acres, and had a stone-masonry wall.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] Gradually, it became filled with mud, and was desilted by Firuz Shah Tughlaq around 1354.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] The autobiographical memoirs of Timur, who invaded Delhi in 1398, mention that the reservoir was a source of water for the city throughout the year.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] In the early years of the 14th century, Alauddin built the Siri Fort.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] The fort walls were mainly constructed using rubble (in mud), although there are some traces of ashlar masonry (in lime and lime plaster).
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] Alauddin camped in Siri during the 1303 Mongol invasion, and after the Mongols left, he built the Qasr-i-Hazar Situn palace at the site of his camp.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] The fortified city of Siri existed in the time of Timur, whose memoirs state that it had seven gates.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] The destruction of the Fort is attributed to the local rulers who removed the fort's stones, bricks and other artifacts for their own buildings.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] In particular, Sher Shah Suri (1540–1545), from Eastern India (Bihar), took away material from Siri to build his own city.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] Alauddin commissioned the Alai Darwaza, which was completed in 1311, and serves as the southern gateway leading to the Quwwat-ul-Islam mosque built by Qutb al-Din Aibak.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] He also started the construction of the Alai Minar, which was intended to be double to size of the Qutb Minar, but the project was abandoned, probably when he died.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] The construction of the Lal Mahal (Red Palace) sandstone building near Chausath Khamba has also been attributed to Alauddin, because its architecture and design is similar to that of the Alai Darwaza.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] In 1311, Alauddin repaired the 100-acre Hauz-i-Shamasi reservoir that had been constructed by Shamsuddin Iltutmish in 1229, and also built a dome at its centre.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] Like his predecessors, Alauddin was a Sunni Muslim.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] His administration persecuted the Ismaili (Shia) minorities, after the orthodox Sunnis falsely accused them of permitting incest in their "secret assemblies".
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] Alauddin ordered an inquiry against them sometime before 1311.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] The inquiry was conducted by the orthodox *ulama*, who found several Ismailis guilty.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] Alauddin ordered the convicts to be sawn into two.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] Ziauddin Barani, writing half a century after his death, mentions that Alauddin did not patronize the Muslim *ulama*, and that "his faith in Islam was firm like the faith of the illiterate and the ignorant".
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] He further states that Alauddin once thought of establishing a new religion.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] Just like the Islamic prophet Muhammad's four Rashidun caliphs helped spread Islam, Alauddin believed that he too had four Khans (Ulugh, Nusrat, Zafar and Alp), with whose help he could establish a new religion.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] Barani's uncle Alaul Mulk convinced him to drop this idea, stating that a new religion could only be found based on a revelation from God, not based on human wisdom.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] Alaul Mulk also argued that even great conquerors like Genghis Khan had not been able to subvert Islam, and people would revolt against Alauddin for founding a new religion.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] Barani's claim that Alauddin thought of founding a religion has been repeated by several later chroniclers as well as later historians.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] Historian Banarsi Prasad Saksena doubts the authenticity of this claim, arguing that it is not supported by Alauddin's contemporary writers.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] According to Barani, Alauddin was the first sultan to separate religion from the state.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] At times, he exploited Muslim fanaticism against Hindu chiefs and the treatment of the *zimmis*.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] Persian historian Wassaf states that he sent an expedition against Gujarat as a holy war and it was not motivated by "lust of conquest".
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] The masnavi *Deval Devi—Khizr Khan* by Amir Khusrau states that Gujarat was only annexed in the second invasion which took place seven years after the first one, implying the first was merely a plundering raid.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] At Khambhat, it is said that the citizens were caught by surprise.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] Alauddin and his generals destroyed several Hindu temples during their military campaigns.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] He compromised with the Hindu chiefs who were willing to accept his suzerainty.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] In a 1305 document, Khusrau mentions that Alauddin treated the obedient Hindu zamindars (feudal landlords) kindly, and granted more favours to them than they had expected.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] In his poetic style, Khusrau states that by this time, all the insolent Hindus in the realm of Hind had died on the battlefield, and the other Hindus had bowed their heads before Alauddin.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] Describing a court held on 19 October 1312, Khusrau writes the ground had become saffron-coloured from the tilaks of the Hindu chiefs bowing before Alauddin.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] This policy of compromise with Hindus was greatly criticized by a small but vocal set of Muslim extremists, as apparent from Barani's writings.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] Alauddin rarely listened to the advice of the orthodox ulama.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] When he had asked about the position of Hindus under an Islamic state, the Qazi Mughisuddin replied that the Hindu "should pay the taxes with meekness and humility coupled with the utmost respect and free from all reluctance.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] Should the collector choose to spit in his mouth, he should open the same without hesitation, so that the official may spit into it...
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] The purport of this extreme meekness and humility on his part... is to show the extreme submissiveness incumbent upon this race.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] God Almighty Himself (in the Quran) commands their complete degradation in as much as these Hindus are the deadliest foes of the true prophet.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] Alauddin believed "that the Hindu will never be submissive and obedient to the Musalman unless he is reduced to abject poverty." He undertook measures to impoverish them and felt it was justified because he knew that the chiefs and *muqaddams* led a luxurious life but never paid a jital in taxes.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] His vigorous and extensive conquests led to him being viewed as persecutor both at home and abroad, including by Maulana Shamsuddin Turk, Abdul Malik Isami and Wassaf.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] Barani, while summing up his achievements, mentions that the submission and obedience of the Hindus during the last decade of his reign had become an established fact.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] He states that such a submission on the part of the Hindus "has neither been seen before nor will be witnessed hereafter".
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] Under the Mamluk dynasty, obtaining a membership in the higher bureaucracy was difficult for the Indian Muslims and impossible for Hindus.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] This however seems to have changed under the Khaljis.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] Khusrau states in *Khazainul Futuh* that Alauddin had dispatched a 30,000 strong army under a Hindu officer Malik Naik, the *Akhur-bek Maisarah*, to repel the Mongols.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] During Ikat Khan's rebellion, the Sultan's life was saved by Hindu soldiers (*paiks*).
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] Because of the large presence of non-Muslims in the imperial army, Alaul Mulk advised him not to leave Delhi to repel the Mongol Qutlugh Khwaja who had surrounded it.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] Per Jain sources, Alauddin held discussions with Jain sages and once specially summoned *Acharya* Mahasena to Delhi.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] There was no learned Digambracarya in North India during this period and Mahasena was persuaded by Jains to defend the faith.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] Alauddin was impressed by his profound learning and asceticism.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] A Digambara Jain Purancandra was very close to him and the Sultan also maintained contacts with the Shwetambara sages.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] The Jain poet *Acharya* Ramachandra Suri was also honored by him.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] Khalji minted coins using the title of *Sikander Sani*.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] Sikander is Old Persian for 'Alexander', a title popularized by Alexander the Great, while sani is Arabic for 'Second'.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] The coin legend (*Sikander-e -Sani*) translates to 'The Second Alexander' in recognition of his military success.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] He had amassed wealth in his treasury through campaigns in Deccan and South India and issued many coins.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] His coins omitted the mention of the Khalifa, replacing it with the self-laudatory title *Sikander-us-sani Yamin-ul-Khilafat*.
[src:gunpowder/alauddin-khalji] He ceased adding Al-Musta'sim's name, instead adding *Yamin-ul-Khilafat Nāsir Amīri 'l-Mu'minīn* (The right hand of the Caliphate, the helper of the Commander of the Faithful).
[src:gunpowder/anfo] The use of ANFO originated in the 1950s.
[src:gunpowder/anfo] It is highly insensitive as an explosive, requiring a quantity of secondary explosive, known as a primer or a booster (larger than a standard blasting cap), in order to be detonated.
[src:gunpowder/anfo] It has found wide use in coal mining, quarrying, metal ore mining, and civil construction in applications where its low cost and ease of use may outweigh the benefits of other explosives, such as water resistance, oxygen balance, higher detonation velocity, or performance in small-diameter columns.
[src:gunpowder/anfo] The mining industry accounts for an estimated 90% of the more than 5.5 million pounds (2.5 thousand tonnes) of explosives used annually in the United States.
[src:gunpowder/anfo] ANFO is also widely used in avalanche hazard mitigation.
[src:gunpowder/anfo] ANFO mixed with nitromethane as the fuel is known as ANNM.
[src:gunpowder/anfo] The chemistry of ANFO detonation is the reaction of ammonium nitrate with a long-chain alkane hydrocarbon (CnH2n+2) to form nitrogen, carbon dioxide, and steam.
[src:gunpowder/anfo] In an ideal stoichiometrically balanced reaction, ANFO is composed of about 94.5% AN and 5.5% FO by weight.
[src:gunpowder/anfo] In practice, a slight excess of fuel oil is added, as underdosing results in reduced performance while overdosing merely results in more post-blast fumes.
[src:gunpowder/anfo] When detonation conditions are optimal, the gases are the only products.
[src:gunpowder/anfo] In practical use, such conditions are impossible to attain, and blasts produce moderate amounts of toxic gases such as carbon monoxide and nitrogen oxides (NOx).
[src:gunpowder/anfo] The fuel component of ANFO is typically diesel fuel, but kerosene, coal dust, racing fuels like nitromethane, or even molasses have been used instead.
[src:gunpowder/anfo] Finely powdered aluminium in the mixture will sensitise it to detonate more readily.
[src:gunpowder/anfo] ANFO is highly insensitive, making it a tertiary explosive (or a "blasting agent").
[src:gunpowder/anfo] Without a sensitizer, it cannot be detonated by a typical blasting cap (such as a No.
[src:gunpowder/anfo] A larger quantity of secondary explosive, known as a primer or a booster, must be used.
[src:gunpowder/anfo] One or two sticks of dynamite were historically used; current practice is to use Tovex or cast boosters of pentolite (TNT/PETN or similar compositions).
[src:gunpowder/anfo] ANFO is technically a high explosive in that it decomposes through detonation rather than deflagration at a velocity higher than the speed of sound in the material, but the low sensitivity means that it is not generally regulated as such.
[src:gunpowder/anfo] ANFO has a moderate velocity compared to other industrial explosives, measuring 3,200 m/s in 130 mm (5 in) diameter, unconfined, at ambient temperature.
[src:gunpowder/anfo] It is described as a *non-ideal high explosive*, as its explosive velocity is far from the thermodynamic ideal due to its porosity and the phase separation of its two components.
[src:gunpowder/anfo] In the mining industry, the term ANFO specifically describes a mixture of solid ammonium nitrate prills and diesel fuel.
[src:gunpowder/anfo] Other explosives based on the ANFO chemistry exist; the most commonly used are emulsions.
[src:gunpowder/anfo] They differ from ANFO in the physical form the reactants take.
[src:gunpowder/anfo] The most notable properties of emulsions are water resistance and higher bulk density.
[src:gunpowder/anfo] While the density of pure crystalline ammonium nitrate is 1700 kg/m3, individual prills of explosive-grade AN measure approximately 1300 kg/m3.
[src:gunpowder/anfo] Their lower density is due to the presence of a small spherical air pocket within each prill: this is the primary difference between AN sold for blasting and that sold for agricultural use.
[src:gunpowder/anfo] These voids are necessary to sensitize ANFO: they create so-called "hot spots".
[src:gunpowder/anfo] Finely powdered aluminium can be added to ANFO to increase both sensitivity and energy; in commercial usages however, this has fallen out of favor due to cost.
[src:gunpowder/anfo] ANFO has a bulk density of about 840 kg/m3.
[src:gunpowder/anfo] In surface mining applications, it is typically loaded into boreholes by dedicated trucks that mix the AN and FO components immediately before the product is dispensed.
[src:gunpowder/anfo] In underground mining applications, ANFO is typically blow-loaded.
[src:gunpowder/anfo] AN is highly hygroscopic, readily absorbing water from air.
[src:gunpowder/anfo] In humid environments, absorbed water interferes with its explosive function.
[src:gunpowder/anfo] AN is fully water-soluble; as such, it cannot be loaded into boreholes that contain standing water.
[src:gunpowder/anfo] When used in wet mining conditions, considerable effort must be taken to remove standing water and install a liner in the borehole; it is generally more productive to instead use a water-resistant explosive such as emulsion.
[src:gunpowder/anfo] Ammonium nitrate is widely used as a fertilizer in the agricultural industry.
[src:gunpowder/anfo] In many countries, its purchase and use are restricted to buyers who have obtained the proper license.
[src:gunpowder/anfo] In most jurisdictions, ammonium nitrate does not need to be classified as an explosive for transport purposes; it is merely an oxidizer.
[src:gunpowder/anfo] Mines typically prepare ANFO on-site using the same diesel fuel that powers their vehicles.
[src:gunpowder/anfo] While many fuels can theoretically be used, the low volatility and cost of diesel make it ideal.
[src:gunpowder/anfo] ANFO under most conditions is detonator-insensitive, so it is legally classified as a blasting agent (tertiary explosive) and not a high explosive.
[src:gunpowder/anfo] Environmental hazards include eutrophication in confined waters and nitrate/gas oil contamination of ground or surface water.
[src:gunpowder/anfo] ANFO was used in 1970 when protests by students became violent at the University of Wisconsin–Madison, who learned how to make and use ANFO from a Wisconsin Conservation Department booklet entitled *Pothole Blasting for Wildlife*, resulting in the Sterling Hall bombing.
[src:gunpowder/anfo] ANFO used to be widely used by the FLNC (National Liberation Front of Corsica), along with f15 explosive.
[src:gunpowder/anfo] Five containers of 500 kilograms (1,100 pounds) each were used to blow up the Tax Office building in Bastia on 28 February 1987.
[src:gunpowder/anfo] The ANFO car bomb was adopted by the Provisional IRA in 1972 and, by 1973, the Troubles were consuming 21,000 kilograms (47,000 pounds) of ammonium nitrate for the majority of bombs.
[src:gunpowder/anfo] The Ulster Volunteer Force (UVF) also made use of ANFO bombs, often mixing in gelignite as a booster, in the Dublin and Monaghan bombings of May 1974 which killed 34 people & injured almost 300, ANFO car bombs were used in Dublin.
[src:gunpowder/anfo] It has also seen use by groups such as the Revolutionary Armed Forces of Colombia and ETA.
[src:gunpowder/anfo] In 1992, Shining Path perpetrated the Tarata bombing in Lima, Peru, using two ANFO truck bombs.
[src:gunpowder/anfo] A similar setup, mixed with nitromethane, was used in the 1995 Oklahoma City bombing by American anti-government extremist Timothy McVeigh and his accomplices to target the Alfred P.
[src:gunpowder/anfo] Murrah Federal Building in Oklahoma City, killing 168 and inuring 684.
[src:gunpowder/anfo] The Shijiazhuang bombings rocked the city of Shijiazhuang, China, on 16 March 2001.
[src:gunpowder/anfo] A total of 108 people were killed, and 38 others injured when, within a short time, several ANFO bombs exploded near four apartment buildings.
[src:gunpowder/anfo] In April 2010, police in Greece confiscated 180 kg of ANFO and other related material stashed in a hideaway in the Athens suburb of Kareas.
[src:gunpowder/anfo] The material was believed to be linked to attacks previously carried out by the "Revolutionary Struggle" terrorist group.
[src:gunpowder/anfo] In January 2010, President Hamid Karzai of Afghanistan also issued a decree banning the use, production, storage, purchase, or sale of ammonium nitrate, after an investigation showed militants in the Taliban insurgency had used the substance in bomb attacks.
[src:gunpowder/anfo] On 22 July 2011, an aluminum powder-enriched ANNM explosive, with total size of 950 kg (150 kg of aluminium powder), increasing demolition power by 10–30% over plain ANFO, was used in the Oslo bombing.
[src:gunpowder/anfo] On 13 April 2016, two suspected IRA members were stopped in Dublin with 67 kg of ANFO.
[src:gunpowder/anfo] On 6 March 2018, eight members of the extreme right neo-Nazi group Combat 18 were arrested in Athens, Greece, accused of multiple attacks on immigrants and activists.
[src:gunpowder/anfo] They had 50 kg of ANFO in their possession.
[src:gunpowder/gunpowder-p01] Gunpowder is classified as a low explosive because of its relatively slow decomposition rate, low ignition temperature and consequently low brisance (breaking/shattering).
[src:gunpowder/gunpowder-p01] Low explosives deflagrate—burning at subsonic speeds—whereas high explosives detonate, producing a supersonic shockwave.
[src:gunpowder/gunpowder-p01] Ignition of gunpowder packed behind a projectile generates enough pressure to force the shot from the muzzle at high speed, but usually not enough force to rupture the gun barrel.
[src:gunpowder/gunpowder-p01] It thus makes a good propellant but is less suitable for shattering rock or fortifications with its low-yield explosive power.
[src:gunpowder/gunpowder-p01] Nonetheless, it was widely used to fill fused artillery shells (and used in mining and civil engineering projects) until the second half of the 19th century, when the first high explosives were put into use.
[src:gunpowder/gunpowder-p01] Gunpowder is one of the Four Great Inventions of China.
[src:gunpowder/gunpowder-p01] Originally developed by Taoists for medicinal purposes, it was first used for warfare around AD 904.
[src:gunpowder/gunpowder-p01] Its use in weapons has declined due to smokeless powder replacing it, whilst its relative inefficiency led to newer alternatives such as dynamite and ammonium nitrate/fuel oil replacing it in industrial applications.
[src:gunpowder/gunpowder-p01] Gunpowder is a low explosive: it does not detonate, but rather deflagrates (burns quickly).
[src:gunpowder/gunpowder-p01] This is an advantage in a propellant device, where one does not desire a shock that would shatter the gun and potentially harm the operator; however, it is a drawback when an explosion is desired.
[src:gunpowder/gunpowder-p01] In that case, the propellant (and most importantly, gases produced by its burning) must be confined.
[src:gunpowder/gunpowder-p01] Since it contains its own oxidizer and additionally burns faster under pressure, its combustion is capable of bursting containers such as a shell, grenade, or improvised "pipe bomb" or "pressure cooker" casings to form shrapnel.
[src:gunpowder/gunpowder-p01] In quarrying, high explosives are generally preferred for shattering rock.
[src:gunpowder/gunpowder-p01] However, because of its low brisance, gunpowder causes fewer fractures and results in more usable stone compared to other explosives, making it useful for blasting slate, which is fragile, or monumental stone such as granite and marble.
[src:gunpowder/gunpowder-p01] Gunpowder is well suited for blank rounds, signal flares, burst charges, and rescue-line launches.
[src:gunpowder/gunpowder-p01] It is also used in fireworks for lifting shells, in rockets as fuel, and in certain special effects.
[src:gunpowder/gunpowder-p01] Combustion converts less than half the mass of gunpowder to gas; most of it turns into particulate matter.
[src:gunpowder/gunpowder-p01] Some of it is ejected, wasting propelling power, fouling the air, and generally being a nuisance (giving away a soldier's position, generating fog that hinders vision, etc.).
[src:gunpowder/gunpowder-p01] Some of it ends up as a thick layer of soot inside the barrel, where it also is a nuisance for subsequent shots, and a cause of jamming an automatic weapon.
[src:gunpowder/gunpowder-p01] Moreover, this residue contains potassium oxide or sodium oxide, which is hygroscopic and forms potassium hydroxide or sodium hydroxide upon absorbing moisture from the air, causing wrought iron or steel gun barrels to corrode.
[src:gunpowder/gunpowder-p01] Gunpowder arms therefore require thorough and regular cleaning to remove the residue.
[src:gunpowder/gunpowder-p01] Gunpowder loads can be used in modern firearms as long as they are not gas-operated.
[src:gunpowder/gunpowder-p01] The most compatible modern guns are smoothbore-barreled shotguns that are long-recoil operated with chrome-plated essential parts such as barrels and bores.
[src:gunpowder/gunpowder-p01] Such guns have minimal fouling and corrosion, and are easier to clean.
[src:gunpowder/gunpowder-p01] The *Taishang Shengzu Jindan Mijue* mentions a formula composed of six parts sulfur to six parts saltpeter to one part birthwort herb.
[src:gunpowder/gunpowder-p01] This experimental medicine origin is reflected in its Chinese name *huoyao* (Chinese: 火药/火藥; pinyin: *huǒ yào*/xuo jɑʊ/), which means "fire medicine".
[src:gunpowder/gunpowder-p01] Saltpeter was known to the Chinese by the mid-1st century AD and was primarily produced in the provinces of Sichuan, Shanxi, and Shandong.
[src:gunpowder/gunpowder-p01] There is strong evidence of the use of saltpeter and sulfur in various medicinal combinations.
[src:gunpowder/gunpowder-p01] The earliest chemical formula for gunpowder appeared in the 11th-century Song dynasty text *Wujing Zongyao* (*Complete Essentials from the Military Classics*), written by Zeng Gongliang between 1040 and 1044.
[src:gunpowder/gunpowder-p01] The *Wujing Zongyao* provides encyclopedia references to a variety of mixtures that included petrochemicals—as well as garlic and honey.
[src:gunpowder/gunpowder-p01] A slow match for flame-throwing mechanisms using the siphon principle and for fireworks and rockets is mentioned.
[src:gunpowder/gunpowder-p01] The mixture formulas in this book contain at most 50% saltpeter — not enough to create an explosion, they produce an incendiary instead.
[src:gunpowder/gunpowder-p01] The *Essentials* was written by a Song dynasty court bureaucrat and there is little evidence that it had any immediate impact on warfare; there is no mention of its use in the chronicles of the wars against the Tanguts in the 11th century, and China was otherwise mostly at peace during this century.
[src:gunpowder/gunpowder-p01] However, it had already been used for fire arrows since at least the 10th century.
[src:gunpowder/gunpowder-p01] Its first recorded military application dates its use to 904 in the form of incendiary projectiles.
[src:gunpowder/gunpowder-p01] In the following centuries the Chinese recognised gunpowder for its military applications and gunpowder was weaponised in the form of bombs, fire lances and hand cannons in China.
[src:gunpowder/gunpowder-p01] Explosive weapons such as bombs have been discovered in a shipwreck off the shore of Japan dated from 1281, during the Mongol invasions of Japan.
[src:gunpowder/gunpowder-p01] By 1083 the Song court was producing hundreds of thousands of fire arrows for their garrisons.
[src:gunpowder/gunpowder-p01] Bombs and the first proto-guns, known as "fire lances", became prominent during the 12th century and were used by the Song during the Jin-Song Wars.
[src:gunpowder/gunpowder-p01] Fire lances were first recorded to have been used at the Siege of De'an in 1132 by Song forces against the Jin.
[src:gunpowder/gunpowder-p01] In the early 13th century the Jin used iron-casing bombs.
[src:gunpowder/gunpowder-p01] Projectiles were added to fire lances, and re-usable fire lance barrels were developed, first out of hardened paper, and then finally, the barrels were made out of metal to better withstand the explosive pressure of gunpowder.
[src:gunpowder/gunpowder-p01] By 1257 some fire lances were firing wads of bullets.
[src:gunpowder/gunpowder-p01] According to Iqtidar Alam Khan, the Mongols introduced gunpowder in their invasion of Persia and Mesopotamia.
[src:gunpowder/gunpowder-p01] The Muslims acquired knowledge of gunpowder sometime between 1240 and 1280, by which point the Syrian Hasan al-Rammah had written recipes, instructions for the purification of saltpeter, and descriptions of gunpowder incendiaries.
[src:gunpowder/gunpowder-p01] However, because al-Rammah attributes his material to "his father and forefathers", Ahmad Y. al-Hassan argues that gunpowder became prevalent in Syria and Egypt by "the end of the twelfth century or the beginning of the thirteenth".
[src:gunpowder/gunpowder-p01] In Persia saltpeter was known as "Chinese salt" (Persian: نمک چینی}, romanized: *namak-i chīnī*) or "salt from Chinese salt marshes" (نمک شوره چینی **namak-i shūra-yi chīnī**).
[src:gunpowder/gunpowder-p01] Hasan al-Rammah included 107 gunpowder recipes in *The Book of Military Horsemanship and Ingenious War Devices* (Arabic: الـفـروسـيـة و الـمـنـاصـب الـحـربـيـة, romanized: *al-Furūsiyya wal-Manāsib al-Ḥarbiyya*), 22 of which are for rockets.
[src:gunpowder/gunpowder-p01] The median of 17 of these 22 compositions for rockets (75% nitrates, 9.06% sulphur, and 15.94% charcoal) are nearly identical to the modern reported ideal recipe of 75% potassium nitrate, 10% sulphur, and 15% charcoal.
[src:gunpowder/gunpowder-p01] The text also mentions fuses, incendiary bombs, naphtha pots, fire lances, and an illustration and description of the earliest torpedo.
[src:gunpowder/gunpowder-p01] The torpedo was called the "egg which moves itself and burns".
[src:gunpowder/gunpowder-p01] Two iron sheets were fastened together and tightened using felt.
[src:gunpowder/gunpowder-p01] The flattened, pear-shaped vessel was filled with gunpowder, metal filings, "good mixtures", two rods, and a large rocket for propulsion.
[src:gunpowder/gunpowder-p01] Judging by the illustration, it was supposed to glide across the water.
[src:gunpowder/gunpowder-p01] Fire lances were used in battles between the Muslims and Mongols in 1299 and 1303.
[src:gunpowder/gunpowder-p01] Al-Hassan claims that in the Battle of Ain Jalut of 1260, the Mamluk Sultanate used "the first cannon in history" against the Mongols, utilizing a formula with near-identical ideal composition ratios for explosive gunpowder.
[src:gunpowder/gunpowder-p01] Other historians urge caution regarding claims of Islamic firearms use in the 1204–1324 period, as late medieval Arabic texts used the same word for gunpowder, *naft*, that they used for an earlier incendiary, naphtha.
[src:gunpowder/gunpowder-p01] The earliest surviving documentary evidence for cannons in the Islamic world is from an Arabic manuscript dated to the early 14th century.
[src:gunpowder/gunpowder-p01] The author's name is uncertain but may have been Shams al-Din Muhammad, who died in 1350.
[src:gunpowder/gunpowder-p01] Dating from around 1320–1350, the illustrations show gunpowder weapons such as gunpowder arrows, bombs, fire tubes, and fire lances or proto-guns.
[src:gunpowder/gunpowder-p01] The manuscript describes a type of gunpowder weapon called a *midfa* which uses gunpowder to shoot projectiles out of a tube at the end of a stock.
[src:gunpowder/gunpowder-p01] Some consider this a cannon, while others do not.
[src:gunpowder/gunpowder-p01] The problem with identifying cannons in early 14th-century Arabic texts is the term *midfa*, which appears from 1342 to 1352 but cannot be proven to be true hand-guns or bombards.
[src:gunpowder/gunpowder-p01] Contemporary accounts of a metal-barrel cannon in the Islamic world do not occur until 1365.
[src:gunpowder/gunpowder-p01] Needham believes that in its original form the term *midfa* refers to the tube or cylinder of a naphtha projector (flamethrower).
[src:gunpowder/gunpowder-p01] After the invention of gunpowder, it meant the tube of fire lances, and eventually it applied to the cylinder of hand-guns and cannons.
[src:gunpowder/gunpowder-p01] Hammer, the Mamluk Sultanate certainly used cannons by 1342.
[src:gunpowder/gunpowder-p01] Lavin, cannons were used by Moors at the siege of Algeciras in 1343.
[src:gunpowder/gunpowder-p01] Shihab al-Din Abu al-Abbas al-Qalqashandi described a metal cannon firing an iron ball between 1365 and 1376.
[src:gunpowder/gunpowder-p01] The musket appeared in the Ottoman Empire by 1465.
[src:gunpowder/gunpowder-p01] In 1598, Chinese writer Zhao Shizhen described Turkish muskets as being superior to European muskets.
[src:gunpowder/gunpowder-p01] The Chinese military work *Wubei Zhi* (1621) later described Turkish muskets that used a rack and pinion mechanism, which was not known to have been used in European or Chinese firearms at the time.
[src:gunpowder/gunpowder-p01] The state-controlled manufacture of gunpowder by the Ottoman Empire through early supply chains to obtain nitre, sulphur and high-quality charcoal from oaks in Anatolia contributed significantly to its expansion between the 15th and 18th centuries.
[src:gunpowder/gunpowder-p01] It was not until later in the 19th century that the systemic production of Turkish gunpowder was reduced considerably, coinciding with the decline of its military might.
[src:gunpowder/gunpowder-p01] The earliest Western accounts of gunpowder appear in texts written by English philosopher Roger Bacon in 1267 called *Opus Majus* and *Opus Tertium*.
[src:gunpowder/gunpowder-p01] The oldest written recipes in continental Europe were recorded under the name Marcus Graecus or Mark the Greek between 1280 and 1300 in the *Liber Ignium*, or *Book of Fires*.
[src:gunpowder/gunpowder-p01] Some sources mention possible gunpowder weapons being deployed by the Mongols against European forces at the Battle of Mohi in 1241.
[src:gunpowder/gunpowder-p01] Professor Kenneth Warren Chase credits the Mongols for introducing into Europe gunpowder and its associated weaponry.
[src:gunpowder/gunpowder-p01] Records show that, in England, gunpowder was being made in 1346 at the Tower of London; a powder house existed at the Tower in 1461, and in 1515 three King's gunpowder makers worked there.
[src:gunpowder/gunpowder-p01] Gunpowder was also being made or stored at other royal castles, such as Portchester.
[src:gunpowder/gunpowder-p01] The English Civil War (1642–1645) led to an expansion of the gunpowder industry, with the repeal of the Royal Patent in August 1641.
[src:gunpowder/gunpowder-p01] In late 14th century Europe, gunpowder was improved by *corning*, the practice of drying it into small clumps to improve combustion and consistency.
[src:gunpowder/gunpowder-p01] During this time, European manufacturers also began regularly purifying saltpeter, using wood ashes containing potassium carbonate to precipitate calcium from their dung liquor, and using ox blood, alum, and slices of turnip to clarify the solution.
[src:gunpowder/gunpowder-p01] During the Renaissance, two European schools of pyrotechnic thought emerged, one in Italy and the other at Nuremberg, Germany.
[src:gunpowder/gunpowder-p01] In Italy, Vannoccio Biringuccio, born in 1480, was a member of the guild *Fraternita di Santa Barbara* but broke with the tradition of secrecy by setting down everything he knew in a book titled *De la pirotechnia*, written in vernacular.
[src:gunpowder/gunpowder-p01] It was published posthumously in 1540, with nine editions over 138 years, and also reprinted by MIT Press in 1966.
[src:gunpowder/gunpowder-p01] By the mid-17th century fireworks were used for entertainment on an unprecedented scale in Europe, being popular even at resorts and public gardens.
[src:gunpowder/gunpowder-p01] With the publication of *Deutliche Anweisung zur Feuerwerkerey* (1748), methods for creating fireworks were sufficiently well-known and well-described that "Firework making has become an exact science." In 1774 Louis XVI ascended to the throne of France at the age of 20.
[src:gunpowder/gunpowder-p01] After he discovered that France was not self-sufficient in gunpowder, a Gunpowder Administration was established; to head it, the lawyer Antoine Lavoisier was appointed.
[src:gunpowder/gunpowder-p01] Although from a bourgeois family, after his degree in law Lavoisier became wealthy from a company set up to collect taxes for the Crown; this allowed him to pursue experimental natural science as a hobby.
[src:gunpowder/gunpowder-p01] Without access to cheap saltpeter (controlled by the British), for hundreds of years France had relied on saltpetremen with royal warrants, the *droit de fouille* or "right to dig", to seize nitrous-containing soil and demolish walls of barnyards, without compensation to the owners.
[src:gunpowder/gunpowder-p01] This caused farmers, the wealthy, or entire villages to bribe the petermen and the associated bureaucracy to leave their buildings alone and the saltpeter uncollected.
[src:gunpowder/gunpowder-p01] Lavoisier instituted a crash program to increase saltpeter production, revised (and later eliminated) the *droit de fouille*, researched best refining and powder manufacturing methods, instituted management and record-keeping, and established pricing that encouraged private investment in works.
[src:gunpowder/gunpowder-p01] Although saltpeter from new Prussian-style putrefaction works had not been produced yet (the process taking about 18 months), in only a year France had gunpowder to export.
[src:gunpowder/gunpowder-p01] A chief beneficiary of this surplus was the American Revolution.
[src:gunpowder/gunpowder-p01] By careful testing and adjusting the proportions and grinding time, powder from mills such as at Essonne outside Paris became the best in the world by 1788, and inexpensive.
[src:gunpowder/gunpowder-p01] Two British physicists, Andrew Noble and Frederick Abel, worked to improve the properties of gunpowder during the late 19th century.
[src:gunpowder/gunpowder-p01] This formed the basis for the Noble-Abel gas equation for internal ballistics.
[src:gunpowder/gunpowder-p01] The introduction of smokeless powder in the late 19th century led to a contraction of the gunpowder industry.
[src:gunpowder/gunpowder-p01] After the end of World War I, the majority of the British gunpowder manufacturers merged into a single company, "Explosives Trades limited", and a number of sites were closed down, including those in Ireland.
[src:gunpowder/gunpowder-p01] This company became Nobel Industries Limited, and in 1926 became a founding member of Imperial Chemical Industries.
[src:gunpowder/gunpowder-p01] The Home Office removed gunpowder from its list of "Permitted Explosives".
[src:gunpowder/gunpowder-p01] Shortly afterwards, on 31 December 1931, the former Curtis & Harvey's Glynneath gunpowder factory at Pontneddfechan in Wales closed down.
[src:gunpowder/gunpowder-p01] The factory was demolished by fire in 1932.
[src:gunpowder/gunpowder-p01] The last remaining gunpowder mill at the Royal Gunpowder Factory, Waltham Abbey was damaged by a German parachute mine in 1941 and it never reopened.
[src:gunpowder/gunpowder-p01] This was followed by the closure and demolition of the gunpowder section at the Royal Ordnance Factory, ROF Chorley, at the end of World War II, and of ICI Nobel's Roslin gunpowder factory which closed in 1954.
[src:gunpowder/gunpowder-p01] This left ICI Nobel's Ardeer site in Scotland, which included a gunpowder factory, as the only factory in Great Britain producing gunpowder.
[src:gunpowder/gunpowder-p01] The gunpowder area of the Ardeer site closed in October 1976.
[src:gunpowder/gunpowder-p01] Gunpowder and gunpowder weapons were transmitted to India through the Mongol invasions of India.
[src:gunpowder/gunpowder-p01] The Mongols were defeated by Alauddin Khalji of the Delhi Sultanate, and some of the Mongol soldiers remained in northern India after their conversion to Islam.
[src:gunpowder/gunpowder-p01] It was written in the *Tarikh-i Firishta* (1606–1607) that Nasiruddin Mahmud the ruler of the Delhi Sultanate presented the envoy of the Mongol ruler Hulegu Khan with a dazzling pyrotechnics display upon his arrival in Delhi in 1258.
[src:gunpowder/gunpowder-p01] Nasiruddin Mahmud tried to express his strength as a ruler and tried to ward off any Mongol attempt similar to the Siege of Baghdad (1258).
[src:gunpowder/gunpowder-p01] Firearms known as *top-o-tufak* also existed in many Muslim kingdoms in India by as early as 1366.
[src:gunpowder/gunpowder-p01] From then on the employment of gunpowder warfare in India was prevalent, with events such as the "Siege of Belgaum" in 1473 by Sultan Muhammad Shah Bahmani.
[src:gunpowder/gunpowder-p01] The shipwrecked Ottoman Admiral Seydi Ali Reis is known to have introduced the earliest type of matchlock weapons, which the Ottomans used against the Portuguese during the Siege of Diu (1531).
[src:gunpowder/gunpowder-p01] After that, a diverse variety of firearms, large guns in particular, became visible in Tanjore, Dacca, Bijapur, and Murshidabad.
[src:gunpowder/gunpowder-p01] Guns made of bronze were recovered from Calicut, the former capital of the Zamorins, in 1504.
[src:gunpowder/gunpowder-p01] The Mughal emperor Akbar mass-produced matchlocks for the Mughal Army.
[src:gunpowder/gunpowder-p01] Akbar is personally known to have shot a leading Rajput commander during the Siege of Chittorgarh.
[src:gunpowder/gunpowder-p01] The Mughals began to use bamboo rockets (mainly for signalling) and employ sappers: special units that undermined heavy stone fortifications to plant gunpowder charges.
[src:gunpowder/gunpowder-p01] The Mughal Emperor Shah Jahan is known to have introduced much more advanced matchlocks, their designs were a combination of Ottoman and Mughal designs.
[src:gunpowder/gunpowder-p01] Shah Jahan also countered the British and other Europeans in his province of Gujarāt, which supplied Europe saltpeter for use in gunpowder warfare during the 17th century.
[src:gunpowder/gunpowder-p01] Bengal and Mālwa participated in saltpeter production.
[src:gunpowder/gunpowder-p01] The Dutch, French, Portuguese, and English used Chhapra as a center of saltpeter refining.
[src:gunpowder/gunpowder-p01] Ever since the founding of the Sultanate of Mysore by Hyder Ali, French military officers were employed to train the Mysore Army.
[src:gunpowder/gunpowder-p01] Hyder Ali and his son Tipu Sultan were the first to introduce modern cannons and muskets, and their army was also the first in India to have official uniforms.
[src:gunpowder/gunpowder-p01] During the Second Anglo-Mysore War Hyder Ali and his son Tipu Sultan unleashed the Mysorean rockets at their British opponents effectively, defeating them on various occasions.
[src:gunpowder/gunpowder-p01] The Mysorean rockets inspired the development of the Congreve rocket, which the British widely used during the Napoleonic Wars and the War of 1812.
[src:gunpowder/gunpowder-p01] Cannons were introduced to Majapahit when Kublai Khan's Chinese army under the leadership of Ike Mese sought to invade Java in 1293.
